00:03:10.020 --> 00:03:13.020
[Amit Varma]: so before we kind of start talking about your book

00:03:13.020 --> 00:03:15.020
[Amit Varma]: tell me a little bit about yourself

00:03:15.020 --> 00:03:16.020
[Amit Varma]: I mean you've written a book on migration

00:03:16.020 --> 00:03:18.020
[Amit Varma]: are you a sort of migrant yourself?

00:03:18.020 --> 00:03:20.020
[Guest]: yeah like pretty much everyone in this city

00:03:20.020 --> 00:03:22.020
[Guest]: pretty much everyone in India

00:03:22.020 --> 00:03:28.020
[Guest]: I think you know migration has hugely influenced my sort of education and career path

00:03:28.020 --> 00:03:30.020
[Guest]: started off in a boarding school

00:03:30.020 --> 00:03:33.020
[Guest]: so you can say I started off you know moving at a very young age

00:03:33.020 --> 00:03:35.020
[Guest]: and I've been pretty much I think in the last six years

00:03:35.020 --> 00:03:37.020
[Guest]: I moved five different cities

00:03:37.020 --> 00:03:40.020
[Guest]: so I've definitely been much more you know on the move

00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:42.020
[Guest]: and that kind of reflects I guess in the book

00:03:42.020 --> 00:03:44.020
[Guest]: and you were trained as a political scientist?

00:03:44.020 --> 00:03:45.020
[Guest]: no trained as an economist

00:03:45.020 --> 00:03:48.020
[Guest]: but I wrote my PhD on migration history

00:03:48.020 --> 00:03:50.020
[Guest]: but it's sort of the economic impact of migration

00:03:50.020 --> 00:03:52.020
[Guest]: and this book in a way is

00:03:52.020 --> 00:03:54.020
[Guest]: after that I did a lot of other research

00:03:54.020 --> 00:03:57.020
[Guest]: and this book is in a way culmination of about 10 years of research

00:03:57.020 --> 00:03:59.020
[Amit Varma]: starting with my PhD

00:03:59.020 --> 00:04:01.020
[Amit Varma]: and one of the things that struck me while reading this book is

00:04:01.020 --> 00:04:03.020
[Amit Varma]: you know I've done a number of episodes with historians

00:04:03.020 --> 00:04:06.020
[Amit Varma]: like Ram Guha, Srinath Raghavan, Manu Pillay

00:04:06.020 --> 00:04:08.020
[Amit Varma]: and one of the things that struck me reading this book is

00:04:08.020 --> 00:04:11.020
[Amit Varma]: that this is really a fairly deeply researched book of history

00:04:11.020 --> 00:04:15.020
[Amit Varma]: as well, was that a sort of skill that you had to train yourself in

00:04:15.020 --> 00:04:17.020
[Amit Varma]: given that you were trained in economics before this?

00:04:17.020 --> 00:04:19.020
[Guest]: absolutely, completely self-trained

00:04:19.020 --> 00:04:21.020
[Guest]: I've never taken a course in history after my class 10

00:04:21.020 --> 00:04:23.020
[Guest]: so history is all about reading a lot

00:04:23.020 --> 00:04:26.020
[Guest]: I spent a year and a half in the US as a house husband

00:04:26.020 --> 00:04:28.020
[Guest]: I just read a lot

00:04:28.020 --> 00:04:30.020
[Guest]: and so I think that really trained me into

00:04:30.020 --> 00:04:32.020
[Guest]: you know reading the core aspect

00:04:32.020 --> 00:04:34.020
[Guest]: of course most of my reading is in economic history

00:04:34.020 --> 00:04:36.020
[Guest]: migration of course is linked heavily into that

00:04:36.020 --> 00:04:39.020
[Guest]: and then I got an opportunity to start teaching history

00:04:39.020 --> 00:04:42.020
[Guest]: at IIM Ahmedabad where I moved in 2016

00:04:42.020 --> 00:04:46.020
[Guest]: and in fact this year we'll be organising a conference on history at IIMA

00:04:46.020 --> 00:04:50.020
[Guest]: so I'm definitely into this field of business economic history

00:04:50.020 --> 00:04:52.020
[Guest]: and migration is a lovely subject

00:04:52.020 --> 00:04:54.020
[Guest]: because you can look at it from practically every discipline

00:04:54.020 --> 00:04:57.020
[Guest]: whether it's law or sociology or economics and so on

00:04:57.020 --> 00:05:00.020
[Guest]: and so my PhD thesis was fairly interdisciplinary

00:05:00.020 --> 00:05:02.020
[Guest]: and so I thought okay I should just extend that

00:05:02.020 --> 00:05:05.020
[Guest]: so though I didn't have a background in history

00:05:05.020 --> 00:05:07.020
[Guest]: I think this reading over the last 10 years

00:05:07.020 --> 00:05:10.020
[Guest]: and then professionally going to different conferences

00:05:10.020 --> 00:05:12.020
[Guest]: and just meeting different people

00:05:12.020 --> 00:05:16.020
[Guest]: has helped tremendously in sort of shaping my thoughts

00:05:16.020 --> 00:05:18.020
[Guest]: when I was studying in London

00:05:18.020 --> 00:05:21.020
[Guest]: they had a department of economics which I was part of

00:05:21.020 --> 00:05:24.020
[Guest]: but I used to audit the courses in the department of economic history

00:05:24.020 --> 00:05:26.020
[Guest]: probably the only university in the world, LSE

00:05:26.020 --> 00:05:29.020
[Guest]: which has a specialised department of economic history

00:05:29.020 --> 00:05:31.020
[Guest]: so I think that's where the interest really got seeded

00:05:31.020 --> 00:05:34.020
[Guest]: and since then I read something on history every day

00:05:34.020 --> 00:05:37.020
[Guest]: and you're right this book is heavily heavily researched

00:05:37.020 --> 00:05:40.020
[Guest]: it cites I think more than 500 studies

00:05:40.020 --> 00:05:43.020
[Guest]: and it's been a lot of fun

00:05:43.020 --> 00:05:47.020
[Guest]: because a lot of the challenge is to get this in an accessible way

00:05:47.020 --> 00:05:50.020
[Guest]: and you know this book I thought

00:05:50.020 --> 00:05:53.020
[Guest]: there should be at least some book which brings out this rich history

00:05:53.020 --> 00:05:55.020
[Amit Varma]: and does the quality of your reading change

00:05:55.020 --> 00:05:57.020
[Amit Varma]: when you know you're writing a book like this

00:05:57.020 --> 00:05:59.020
[Amit Varma]: and let's say you're reading partly for pleasure

00:05:59.020 --> 00:06:00.020
[Amit Varma]: because obviously you love the subject

00:06:00.020 --> 00:06:03.020
[Amit Varma]: but also you're reading to gather in all the information

00:06:03.020 --> 00:06:04.020
[Amit Varma]: does it change the way you read?

00:06:04.020 --> 00:06:06.020
[Amit Varma]: Do you stop more often to take notes

00:06:06.020 --> 00:06:08.020
[Amit Varma]: or to you know look at the bibliography

00:06:08.020 --> 00:06:09.020
[Amit Varma]: and get those other books?

00:06:09.020 --> 00:06:10.020
[Amit Varma]: How does it work?

00:06:10.020 --> 00:06:12.020
[Guest]: Yeah I mean I think this is

00:06:12.020 --> 00:06:14.020
[Guest]: I call this a semi-academic book

00:06:14.020 --> 00:06:15.020
[Guest]: so it's got the academic stuff

00:06:15.020 --> 00:06:18.020
[Guest]: but it's also written for the general audience

00:06:18.020 --> 00:06:19.020
[Guest]: and so the more challenging part

00:06:19.020 --> 00:06:21.020
[Guest]: I think the academic stuff is simpler

00:06:21.020 --> 00:06:22.020
[Guest]: in the sense you get some books

00:06:22.020 --> 00:06:24.020
[Guest]: you know you make some notes and that's fine

00:06:24.020 --> 00:06:26.020
[Guest]: but it's really how do you intersperse popular culture

00:06:26.020 --> 00:06:29.020
[Guest]: how do you get the sort of really day-to-day anecdotes

00:06:29.020 --> 00:06:31.020
[Guest]: conversations into the book

00:06:31.020 --> 00:06:34.020
[Guest]: and there's so much that one can get in a book on migration

00:06:34.020 --> 00:06:36.020
[Guest]: but one has to be really selective

00:06:36.020 --> 00:06:37.020
[Guest]: and so that has you know

00:06:37.020 --> 00:06:39.020
[Guest]: that's I think taken more time

00:06:39.020 --> 00:06:41.020
[Guest]: in passing through a variety of things

00:06:41.020 --> 00:06:42.020
[Guest]: for example songs

00:06:42.020 --> 00:06:44.020
[Guest]: there's so many songs on migration

00:06:44.020 --> 00:06:46.020
[Amit Varma]: but I've chosen some which I thought you know

00:06:46.020 --> 00:06:47.020
[Amit Varma]: exactly

00:06:47.020 --> 00:06:50.020
[Guest]: so I thought that was an iconic song of migration

00:06:50.020 --> 00:06:51.020
[Guest]: and it's really worked

00:06:51.020 --> 00:06:53.020
[Guest]: because I actually asked around

00:06:53.020 --> 00:06:54.020
[Guest]: I chose a few songs

00:06:54.020 --> 00:06:56.020
[Guest]: and then this song seemed to be

00:06:56.020 --> 00:06:57.020
[Guest]: of course it was apt

00:06:57.020 --> 00:06:59.020
[Guest]: because I was talking about Burma in that chapter

00:06:59.020 --> 00:07:01.020
[Guest]: but that song it's incredible

00:07:01.020 --> 00:07:02.020
[Guest]: the resonance I received

00:07:02.020 --> 00:07:04.020
[Guest]: people across India have said you know

00:07:04.020 --> 00:07:05.020
[Guest]: that song is

00:07:05.020 --> 00:07:07.020
[Guest]: or they've just flipped through the book

00:07:07.020 --> 00:07:08.020
[Guest]: and bought the book because this song

00:07:08.020 --> 00:07:09.020
[Guest]: it's on that particular quote

00:07:09.020 --> 00:07:11.020
[Amit Varma]: and it's really resonant at multiple levels

00:07:11.020 --> 00:07:14.020
[Amit Varma]: because a lot of the questions I'm going to ask you later

00:07:14.020 --> 00:07:16.020
[Amit Varma]: can easily you know go back to that song

00:07:16.020 --> 00:07:19.020
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that it sort of shows the loneliness

00:07:19.020 --> 00:07:21.020
[Amit Varma]: and the longing you feel for a loved one

00:07:21.020 --> 00:07:24.020
[Amit Varma]: it also sort of is almost a commentary on gender

00:07:24.020 --> 00:07:26.020
[Amit Varma]: in the sense it's a wife who's left back

00:07:26.020 --> 00:07:27.020
[Amit Varma]: and it's a husband who's gone

00:07:27.020 --> 00:07:31.020
[Amit Varma]: and also to me it never really struck me

00:07:31.020 --> 00:07:33.020
[Amit Varma]: because I'm born in a generation as are you

00:07:33.020 --> 00:07:36.020
[Amit Varma]: where Indians don't really migrate to Rangoon anymore

00:07:36.020 --> 00:07:38.020
[Amit Varma]: and reading your book in that sense

00:07:38.020 --> 00:07:41.020
[Amit Varma]: was a revelation in terms of figuring out

00:07:41.020 --> 00:07:46.020
[Amit Varma]: that you know Burma was such a huge source of Indian migration

00:07:46.020 --> 00:07:48.020
[Guest]: yeah absolutely I mean Burma

00:07:48.020 --> 00:07:49.020
[Guest]: for the east coast

00:07:49.020 --> 00:07:52.020
[Guest]: it was like what today the Persian Gulf is for the west coast

00:07:52.020 --> 00:07:55.020
[Guest]: Rangoon 100 years back is what we see Dubai today

00:07:55.020 --> 00:07:59.020
[Guest]: it's almost like a mirror image 100 years back and today

00:07:59.020 --> 00:08:00.020
[Guest]: and you know people

00:08:00.020 --> 00:08:02.020
[Guest]: even if you look at the city of Mumbai

00:08:02.020 --> 00:08:04.020
[Guest]: I mean the diamond dealers like Ketan Mehta

00:08:04.020 --> 00:08:06.020
[Guest]: after his wife this Leelavati hospital is built

00:08:06.020 --> 00:08:08.020
[Guest]: Ketan Mehta started off in Burma

00:08:08.020 --> 00:08:12.020
[Guest]: and then you know a lot of people had to leave Burma eventually

00:08:12.020 --> 00:08:14.020
[Guest]: so a lot of capital was there in Burma

00:08:14.020 --> 00:08:15.020
[Guest]: different communities

00:08:15.020 --> 00:08:17.020
[Guest]: I mean of course a lot of people are jailed as well

00:08:17.020 --> 00:08:20.020
[Guest]: Burma had a famous jail tilak most famously was there

00:08:20.020 --> 00:08:22.020
[Guest]: and let's not forget that the last king of Burma himself

00:08:22.020 --> 00:08:25.020
[Guest]: was exiled in Ratnagiri which is not too far from here

00:08:25.020 --> 00:08:27.020
[Amit Varma]: in fact you point out the very interesting parallel

00:08:27.020 --> 00:08:30.020
[Amit Varma]: that you know tilak was a migrant from Ratnagiri

00:08:30.020 --> 00:08:31.020
[Amit Varma]: and when he was jailed in Burma

00:08:31.020 --> 00:08:33.020
[Guest]: the king of Burma was jailed in Ratnagiri

00:08:33.020 --> 00:08:34.020
[Guest]: yeah absolutely at the same time

00:08:34.020 --> 00:08:35.020
[Amit Varma]: yeah that's pretty wild

00:08:35.020 --> 00:08:36.020
[Amit Varma]: getting to your book

00:08:36.020 --> 00:08:39.020
[Amit Varma]: you begin by pointing out that there are traditionally

00:08:39.020 --> 00:08:40.020
[Amit Varma]: two routes to diversity

00:08:40.020 --> 00:08:42.020
[Amit Varma]: which are basically

00:08:42.020 --> 00:08:43.020
[Amit Varma]: one is through migration

00:08:43.020 --> 00:08:45.020
[Amit Varma]: and the other is through isolation

00:08:45.020 --> 00:08:47.020
[Amit Varma]: and the lack of migration

00:08:47.020 --> 00:08:50.020
[Amit Varma]: and you point out that there's often been a misconception

00:08:50.020 --> 00:08:53.020
[Amit Varma]: about what makes India so diverse

00:08:53.020 --> 00:08:55.020
[Amit Varma]: and that is one sort and not the other

00:08:55.020 --> 00:08:56.020
[Guest]: can you elaborate?

00:08:56.020 --> 00:08:57.020
[Guest]: yeah I mean

00:08:57.020 --> 00:08:59.020
[Guest]: you know if you look at languages for example

00:08:59.020 --> 00:09:02.020
[Guest]: we feel that we're very proud that India is such a diverse country

00:09:02.020 --> 00:09:03.020
[Guest]: but actually there's some

00:09:03.020 --> 00:09:04.020
[Guest]: like there's Papua New Guinea

00:09:04.020 --> 00:09:06.020
[Guest]: which has more languages than India

00:09:06.020 --> 00:09:07.020
[Guest]: and that's because the islands never talked to each other

00:09:07.020 --> 00:09:10.020
[Guest]: they didn't have the sort of technology to bridge that

00:09:10.020 --> 00:09:11.020
[Guest]: so the question is you know

00:09:11.020 --> 00:09:13.020
[Guest]: in India we know for a fact

00:09:13.020 --> 00:09:14.020
[Guest]: that communities are very isolated

00:09:14.020 --> 00:09:16.020
[Guest]: in the sense even today

00:09:16.020 --> 00:09:18.020
[Guest]: inter-community marriages are very

00:09:18.020 --> 00:09:19.020
[Guest]: practically non-existent

00:09:19.020 --> 00:09:20.020
[Guest]: as per some survey

00:09:20.020 --> 00:09:22.020
[Guest]: the India Human Development Survey

00:09:22.020 --> 00:09:24.020
[Guest]: large nationally representative survey

00:09:24.020 --> 00:09:27.020
[Guest]: something like 94% of Indians still marry

00:09:27.020 --> 00:09:29.020
[Guest]: within their own castes and communities

00:09:29.020 --> 00:09:32.020
[Guest]: so this is a very highly endogamous society

00:09:32.020 --> 00:09:34.020
[Guest]: but what's interesting is

00:09:34.020 --> 00:09:36.020
[Guest]: even though people are marrying within their groups

00:09:36.020 --> 00:09:37.020
[Guest]: they're still moving

00:09:37.020 --> 00:09:39.020
[Guest]: and in that process

00:09:39.020 --> 00:09:42.020
[Guest]: there's a transfer of language, culture, customs

00:09:42.020 --> 00:09:43.020
[Guest]: so what I argue is

00:09:43.020 --> 00:09:45.020
[Guest]: I mean is this

00:09:45.020 --> 00:09:46.020
[Guest]: what I ask is that

00:09:46.020 --> 00:09:48.020
[Guest]: is it the case that all these communities

00:09:48.020 --> 00:09:50.020
[Guest]: were sitting isolated

00:09:50.020 --> 00:09:51.020
[Guest]: and you know bang

00:09:51.020 --> 00:09:52.020
[Guest]: you have the British coming

00:09:52.020 --> 00:09:53.020
[Guest]: and then you have independence

00:09:53.020 --> 00:09:56.020
[Guest]: and then they've been forged into a common nation

00:09:56.020 --> 00:09:58.020
[Guest]: and what I find is actually that

00:09:58.020 --> 00:09:59.020
[Guest]: people have been on the move

00:09:59.020 --> 00:10:00.020
[Guest]: whether it's for

00:10:00.020 --> 00:10:01.020
[Guest]: and not just for pilgrimage

00:10:01.020 --> 00:10:02.020
[Guest]: they've been moving for work

00:10:02.020 --> 00:10:04.020
[Guest]: they've been moving for a variety of reasons

00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:06.020
[Guest]: and the most fundamental form of migration

00:10:06.020 --> 00:10:08.020
[Guest]: of course is marriage

00:10:08.020 --> 00:10:10.020
[Guest]: and more women have moved

00:10:10.020 --> 00:10:11.020
[Guest]: permanently in India than men

00:10:11.020 --> 00:10:12.020
[Guest]: for marriage

00:10:12.020 --> 00:10:15.020
[Guest]: and it's not necessarily just the neighboring village

00:10:15.020 --> 00:10:16.020
[Guest]: so they also go

00:10:16.020 --> 00:10:18.020
[Guest]: you know at least 100 kilometers

00:10:18.020 --> 00:10:19.020
[Guest]: many paths

00:10:19.020 --> 00:10:22.020
[Guest]: and because it's strong sun preference in some parts

00:10:22.020 --> 00:10:24.020
[Guest]: women are moving

00:10:24.020 --> 00:10:26.020
[Guest]: more than 100 kilometers in many places

00:10:26.020 --> 00:10:29.020
[Guest]: and it's actually these small small migrations

00:10:29.020 --> 00:10:30.020
[Guest]: which at the margin

00:10:30.020 --> 00:10:32.020
[Guest]: are spreading or diffusing different cultures

00:10:32.020 --> 00:10:34.020
[Guest]: especially when you see linguistic overlap

00:10:34.020 --> 00:10:37.020
[Guest]: so where does a Kannada speaking boundary end

00:10:37.020 --> 00:10:38.020
[Guest]: and where does a Marathi speaker

00:10:38.020 --> 00:10:40.020
[Guest]: or where does a Telugu speaker start

00:10:40.020 --> 00:10:42.020
[Guest]: these sort of

00:10:42.020 --> 00:10:44.020
[Guest]: these marginal linguistic boundaries

00:10:44.020 --> 00:10:46.020
[Guest]: are in a way sort of

00:10:46.020 --> 00:10:49.020
[Guest]: you know massaged through these marriage migrations

00:10:49.020 --> 00:10:51.020
[Guest]: because it's the woman of the household

00:10:51.020 --> 00:10:53.020
[Guest]: who often marries into a different linguistic background

00:10:53.020 --> 00:10:55.020
[Guest]: same caste but different linguistic

00:10:55.020 --> 00:10:57.020
[Guest]: and she learns the language

00:10:57.020 --> 00:10:59.020
[Guest]: and so this is a sort of bridge

00:10:59.020 --> 00:11:00.020
[Guest]: it's a very subtle bridge

00:11:00.020 --> 00:11:02.020
[Guest]: nobody sees this as migration

00:11:02.020 --> 00:11:04.020
[Guest]: but it's actually these millions of women migrations

00:11:04.020 --> 00:11:06.020
[Guest]: on almost a day to day basis

00:11:06.020 --> 00:11:08.020
[Guest]: that actually what I argue is

00:11:08.020 --> 00:11:09.020
[Guest]: the invisible threads

00:11:09.020 --> 00:11:11.020
[Guest]: that hold India's diversity

00:11:11.020 --> 00:11:12.020
[Guest]: to paraphrase Nehru

00:11:12.020 --> 00:11:14.020
[Amit Varma]: and I guess along with the languages

00:11:14.020 --> 00:11:16.020
[Amit Varma]: it's also an intermingling of other parts of culture

00:11:16.020 --> 00:11:17.020
[Amit Varma]: like our cuisines

00:11:17.020 --> 00:11:18.020
[Amit Varma]: absolutely

00:11:18.020 --> 00:11:20.020
[Amit Varma]: you know all of which is a melting pot

00:11:20.020 --> 00:11:21.020
[Amit Varma]: I mean I'll come back to caste later

00:11:21.020 --> 00:11:23.020
[Amit Varma]: because you've got a lot of insights on that

00:11:23.020 --> 00:11:24.020
[Amit Varma]: in your book

00:11:24.020 --> 00:11:26.020
[Amit Varma]: and what you just kind of said about endogamy

00:11:26.020 --> 00:11:28.020
[Amit Varma]: reminded me of a quote from David Reich's book

00:11:28.020 --> 00:11:30.020
[Amit Varma]: Who We Are and How We Got Here

00:11:30.020 --> 00:11:31.020
[Amit Varma]: where he speaks about how

00:11:31.020 --> 00:11:33.020
[Amit Varma]: India is not really one large population

00:11:33.020 --> 00:11:34.020
[Amit Varma]: in his words

00:11:34.020 --> 00:11:36.020
[Amit Varma]: the Han Chinese would be one large population

00:11:36.020 --> 00:11:39.020
[Amit Varma]: India is really a collection of many many many small populations

00:11:39.020 --> 00:11:41.020
[Amit Varma]: because of the caste system

00:11:41.020 --> 00:11:43.020
[Amit Varma]: over the last 2000 years

00:11:43.020 --> 00:11:45.020
[Amit Varma]: there's been very little intermarriage

00:11:45.020 --> 00:11:47.020
[Amit Varma]: but as you're pointing out

00:11:47.020 --> 00:11:50.020
[Amit Varma]: that doesn't mean that there hasn't been intermingling of cultures

00:11:50.020 --> 00:11:52.020
[Amit Varma]: there has been a whole amount

00:11:52.020 --> 00:11:53.020
[Amit Varma]: and a lot of that is

00:11:53.020 --> 00:11:55.020
[Amit Varma]: because of migration

00:11:55.020 --> 00:11:57.020
[Amit Varma]: now about 3 months back

00:11:57.020 --> 00:11:58.020
[Amit Varma]: I did an episode with Tony Joseph

00:11:58.020 --> 00:11:59.020
[Amit Varma]: on his book The Early Indians

00:11:59.020 --> 00:12:02.020
[Amit Varma]: which is also I guess in a sense about migration

00:12:02.020 --> 00:12:03.020
[Amit Varma]: absolutely

00:12:03.020 --> 00:12:04.020
[Amit Varma]: but that kind of covers early India

00:12:04.020 --> 00:12:05.020
[Amit Varma]: so you get a sense of

00:12:05.020 --> 00:12:06.020
[Amit Varma]: ok you know

00:12:06.020 --> 00:12:08.020
[Amit Varma]: there was a migration out of Africa

00:12:08.020 --> 00:12:09.020
[Amit Varma]: and then

00:12:09.020 --> 00:12:11.020
[Amit Varma]: there was the Indus Valley Civilization

00:12:11.020 --> 00:12:12.020
[Amit Varma]: which was the early Indians

00:12:12.020 --> 00:12:14.020
[Amit Varma]: and the sort of estations

00:12:14.020 --> 00:12:16.020
[Amit Varma]: and then later you have the Aryan Migration

00:12:16.020 --> 00:12:17.020
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth

00:12:17.020 --> 00:12:20.020
[Amit Varma]: and that's kind of where his book leaves off

00:12:20.020 --> 00:12:21.020
[Amit Varma]: having covered that part

00:12:21.020 --> 00:12:24.020
[Amit Varma]: and you sort of mentioned that briefly in your first chapter

00:12:24.020 --> 00:12:27.020
[Amit Varma]: but you know then you sort of go on to talk about

00:12:27.020 --> 00:12:30.020
[Amit Varma]: how forces like geography and the weather

00:12:30.020 --> 00:12:33.020
[Amit Varma]: shaped migration from that part on

00:12:33.020 --> 00:12:36.020
[Amit Varma]: and particularly how the Indo-Gangetic Plane

00:12:36.020 --> 00:12:39.020
[Amit Varma]: which is a sort of a hub and spoke

00:12:39.020 --> 00:12:42.020
[Amit Varma]: of all the migrations that have been happening here

00:12:42.020 --> 00:12:44.020
[Amit Varma]: which now contains 10% of the world's population

00:12:44.020 --> 00:12:46.020
[Amit Varma]: how the center kind of shifted there

00:12:46.020 --> 00:12:47.020
[Amit Varma]: can you talk a bit about that?

00:12:47.020 --> 00:12:49.020
[Guest]: Yeah, we still don't know exactly

00:12:49.020 --> 00:12:51.020
[Guest]: how or when this center shifted

00:12:51.020 --> 00:12:53.020
[Guest]: from the Indus Valley to Bihar

00:12:53.020 --> 00:12:54.020
[Guest]: but as I say

00:12:54.020 --> 00:12:56.020
[Guest]: two of the most famous migrants

00:12:56.020 --> 00:12:58.020
[Guest]: arguably are Buddha and Mahavir

00:12:58.020 --> 00:12:59.020
[Guest]: both associated with Bihar

00:12:59.020 --> 00:13:01.020
[Guest]: not necessarily born there

00:13:01.020 --> 00:13:03.020
[Guest]: and what's fascinating for me is that

00:13:03.020 --> 00:13:06.020
[Guest]: today Bihar is the epitome of out-migration

00:13:06.020 --> 00:13:08.020
[Guest]: whereas 2000 years back

00:13:08.020 --> 00:13:10.020
[Guest]: it was arguably you know

00:13:10.020 --> 00:13:13.020
[Guest]: the sort of Asia's number one hotbed for in-migration

00:13:13.020 --> 00:13:15.020
[Guest]: you had students visiting Nalanda University

00:13:15.020 --> 00:13:17.020
[Guest]: from far and so on

00:13:17.020 --> 00:13:19.020
[Guest]: so this is a really rich culture

00:13:19.020 --> 00:13:20.020
[Guest]: it's very dense

00:13:20.020 --> 00:13:22.020
[Guest]: which it is even today

00:13:22.020 --> 00:13:24.020
[Guest]: and it's a culture which is kind of

00:13:24.020 --> 00:13:26.020
[Guest]: you know probably relatively much richer

00:13:26.020 --> 00:13:27.020
[Guest]: than the rest

00:13:27.020 --> 00:13:29.020
[Guest]: and it's gone into relative decline

00:13:29.020 --> 00:13:31.020
[Guest]: over several centuries

00:13:31.020 --> 00:13:34.020
[Guest]: these migrations have happened through

00:13:34.020 --> 00:13:35.020
[Guest]: multiple kinds

00:13:35.020 --> 00:13:38.020
[Guest]: one of course is through the wandering ascetic

00:13:38.020 --> 00:13:39.020
[Guest]: so that's the pilgrimage

00:13:39.020 --> 00:13:41.020
[Guest]: and you know variety of forms

00:13:41.020 --> 00:13:42.020
[Guest]: but there's a particular social group

00:13:42.020 --> 00:13:43.020
[Guest]: called the Brahmanas

00:13:43.020 --> 00:13:45.020
[Guest]: which in the first millennium is very important

00:13:45.020 --> 00:13:47.020
[Guest]: and in a way you can't understand

00:13:47.020 --> 00:13:48.020
[Guest]: the spread of Hindu thought

00:13:48.020 --> 00:13:50.020
[Guest]: Hindu philosophy consolidation

00:13:50.020 --> 00:13:53.020
[Guest]: without understanding the travels of Shankaracharya

00:13:53.020 --> 00:13:55.020
[Guest]: or understanding even the geography

00:13:55.020 --> 00:13:56.020
[Guest]: of the Indian subcontinent

00:13:56.020 --> 00:13:57.020
[Guest]: where you have these four martyrs

00:13:57.020 --> 00:13:58.020
[Guest]: placed in four different corners

00:13:58.020 --> 00:14:00.020
[Guest]: they kind of map out the geography

00:14:00.020 --> 00:14:02.020
[Guest]: and this is important because actually

00:14:02.020 --> 00:14:04.020
[Guest]: we don't have good records of maps

00:14:04.020 --> 00:14:06.020
[Guest]: before the arrival of the Europeans

00:14:06.020 --> 00:14:08.020
[Guest]: actually no record

00:14:08.020 --> 00:14:11.020
[Guest]: that we visually mapped out spaces

00:14:11.020 --> 00:14:13.020
[Guest]: but clearly we were very good with directions

00:14:13.020 --> 00:14:14.020
[Guest]: and we knew you know

00:14:14.020 --> 00:14:16.020
[Guest]: how to get from one place to the other

00:14:16.020 --> 00:14:18.020
[Guest]: so this migration of the social group

00:14:18.020 --> 00:14:19.020
[Guest]: Brahmana is very interesting

00:14:19.020 --> 00:14:21.020
[Guest]: because they were given orders by the king

00:14:21.020 --> 00:14:23.020
[Guest]: to go and settle down

00:14:23.020 --> 00:14:25.020
[Guest]: and collect taxes from people

00:14:25.020 --> 00:14:28.020
[Guest]: and so this is the first real record

00:14:28.020 --> 00:14:30.020
[Guest]: that we have of migration

00:14:30.020 --> 00:14:31.020
[Guest]: that comes in the first millennium

00:14:31.020 --> 00:14:32.020
[Guest]: now you can argue that

00:14:32.020 --> 00:14:34.020
[Guest]: almost every war required some migration

00:14:34.020 --> 00:14:36.020
[Guest]: marriage would require some migration

00:14:36.020 --> 00:14:38.020
[Guest]: but something which is mentioned

00:14:38.020 --> 00:14:39.020
[Guest]: clearly in the scriptures

00:14:39.020 --> 00:14:42.020
[Guest]: as to so and so move from here to here

00:14:42.020 --> 00:14:43.020
[Guest]: comes from this migration

00:14:43.020 --> 00:14:44.020
[Guest]: of this particular social group

00:14:44.020 --> 00:14:45.020
[Guest]: and I would argue that

00:14:45.020 --> 00:14:47.020
[Guest]: this is very important to understand

00:14:47.020 --> 00:14:48.020
[Guest]: how Hindu sort of thought

00:14:48.020 --> 00:14:51.020
[Guest]: really consolidated in the subcontinent

00:14:51.020 --> 00:14:52.020
[Guest]: because we think today that

00:14:52.020 --> 00:14:54.020
[Guest]: you know Hinduism is for example

00:14:54.020 --> 00:14:55.020
[Guest]: the default

00:14:55.020 --> 00:14:56.020
[Guest]: but in the first millennium

00:14:56.020 --> 00:14:57.020
[Guest]: there were actually various philosophical thoughts

00:14:57.020 --> 00:14:59.020
[Guest]: we could have been a completely Jain country

00:14:59.020 --> 00:15:01.020
[Guest]: we could have been a completely Buddhist country

00:15:01.020 --> 00:15:03.020
[Guest]: but ultimately as we say

00:15:03.020 --> 00:15:06.020
[Guest]: about 70% or 80% of the subcontinent today

00:15:06.020 --> 00:15:07.020
[Guest]: is Hindu

00:15:07.020 --> 00:15:09.020
[Guest]: and these migrations were important

00:15:09.020 --> 00:15:10.020
[Guest]: to consolidate

00:15:10.020 --> 00:15:12.020
[Amit Varma]: and were these migrations of the Brahmanas

00:15:12.020 --> 00:15:13.020
[Amit Varma]: purposeful in that sense

00:15:13.020 --> 00:15:14.020
[Amit Varma]: that you know

00:15:14.020 --> 00:15:17.020
[Amit Varma]: a sort of a religious colonialism

00:15:17.020 --> 00:15:18.020
[Amit Varma]: that we want to spread Hinduism

00:15:18.020 --> 00:15:20.020
[Amit Varma]: and this is how we do it

00:15:20.020 --> 00:15:21.020
[Amit Varma]: was it kind of purposeful in that way?

00:15:21.020 --> 00:15:23.020
[Guest]: I don't think we have enough evidence of that

00:15:23.020 --> 00:15:24.020
[Guest]: but clearly these were

00:15:24.020 --> 00:15:26.020
[Guest]: you can call it land-based colonialism

00:15:26.020 --> 00:15:27.020
[Guest]: in the sense that

00:15:27.020 --> 00:15:29.020
[Guest]: they were given villages

00:15:29.020 --> 00:15:30.020
[Guest]: to sort of maintain

00:15:30.020 --> 00:15:31.020
[Guest]: collect taxes

00:15:31.020 --> 00:15:33.020
[Guest]: and of course send the taxes back

00:15:33.020 --> 00:15:34.020
[Guest]: so we know that you know

00:15:34.020 --> 00:15:35.020
[Guest]: there's a relationship between

00:15:35.020 --> 00:15:36.020
[Guest]: where the people are going

00:15:36.020 --> 00:15:37.020
[Guest]: and the sort of metropole

00:15:37.020 --> 00:15:39.020
[Guest]: and you have numerous inscriptions

00:15:39.020 --> 00:15:40.020
[Guest]: there are many books written on this

00:15:40.020 --> 00:15:41.020
[Guest]: but especially Orissa

00:15:41.020 --> 00:15:42.020
[Guest]: I mean if you ask

00:15:42.020 --> 00:15:43.020
[Guest]: you know why does Orissa have

00:15:43.020 --> 00:15:44.020
[Guest]: so many of these temples

00:15:44.020 --> 00:15:46.020
[Guest]: and centers which came

00:15:46.020 --> 00:15:48.020
[Guest]: and you find a lot of these inscriptions

00:15:48.020 --> 00:15:49.020
[Guest]: suggest that

00:15:49.020 --> 00:15:50.020
[Guest]: there was this massive migration

00:15:50.020 --> 00:15:51.020
[Guest]: towards Orissa

00:15:51.020 --> 00:15:53.020
[Guest]: sometime in this first millennium

00:15:53.020 --> 00:15:55.020
[Guest]: these are the stray references

00:15:55.020 --> 00:15:56.020
[Guest]: to migration

00:15:56.020 --> 00:15:57.020
[Guest]: they are the outsiders

00:15:57.020 --> 00:15:58.020
[Guest]: so for example

00:15:58.020 --> 00:15:59.020
[Guest]: even Alexander's armies

00:15:59.020 --> 00:16:01.020
[Guest]: there's references to Indians

00:16:01.020 --> 00:16:02.020
[Guest]: being taken back

00:16:02.020 --> 00:16:04.020
[Guest]: to Europe as soldiers and so on

00:16:04.020 --> 00:16:05.020
[Guest]: and when I was doing research

00:16:05.020 --> 00:16:06.020
[Guest]: on this period

00:16:06.020 --> 00:16:07.020
[Guest]: I found it's very interesting

00:16:07.020 --> 00:16:08.020
[Guest]: because you never really think

00:16:08.020 --> 00:16:09.020
[Guest]: of Indians being in Europe

00:16:09.020 --> 00:16:11.020
[Guest]: 2000 years back

00:16:11.020 --> 00:16:12.020
[Guest]: but apparently some of them were

00:16:12.020 --> 00:16:13.020
[Guest]: you know

00:16:13.020 --> 00:16:14.020
[Guest]: maybe a handful

00:16:14.020 --> 00:16:17.020
[Guest]: but there are actually references to that

00:16:17.020 --> 00:16:18.020
[Amit Varma]: in fact you've got a reference

00:16:18.020 --> 00:16:19.020
[Amit Varma]: somewhere in your book

00:16:19.020 --> 00:16:20.020
[Amit Varma]: if I remember correctly

00:16:20.020 --> 00:16:21.020
[Amit Varma]: to 15,000 people in Armenia

00:16:21.020 --> 00:16:22.020
[Amit Varma]: yes

00:16:22.020 --> 00:16:24.020
[Amit Varma]: which was pretty wild

00:16:24.020 --> 00:16:25.020
[Amit Varma]: because I'd be like

00:16:25.020 --> 00:16:26.020
[Amit Varma]: are there 15,000 Indians

00:16:26.020 --> 00:16:27.020
[Amit Varma]: in Armenia today?

00:16:27.020 --> 00:16:28.020
[Guest]: No, I doubt it

00:16:28.020 --> 00:16:29.020
[Guest]: yeah

00:16:29.020 --> 00:16:30.020
[Guest]: and it's one of those mysteries

00:16:30.020 --> 00:16:31.020
[Guest]: because

00:16:32.020 --> 00:16:33.020
[Guest]: it's always tough

00:16:33.020 --> 00:16:34.020
[Guest]: to understand exact numbers

00:16:34.020 --> 00:16:35.020
[Guest]: but

00:16:35.020 --> 00:16:36.020
[Guest]: this is one of those

00:16:36.020 --> 00:16:37.020
[Guest]: loose ends

00:16:37.020 --> 00:16:38.020
[Guest]: where we

00:16:38.020 --> 00:16:39.020
[Guest]: there's some evidence

00:16:39.020 --> 00:16:40.020
[Guest]: that people were there

00:16:40.020 --> 00:16:41.020
[Guest]: but we don't know

00:16:41.020 --> 00:16:42.020
[Guest]: what happened after

00:16:42.020 --> 00:16:43.020
[Guest]: so they were either wiped out

00:16:43.020 --> 00:16:44.020
[Guest]: or they got completely assimilated

00:16:44.020 --> 00:16:45.020
[Guest]: or converted

00:16:45.020 --> 00:16:46.020
[Guest]: we don't know

00:16:46.020 --> 00:16:48.020
[Guest]: and there are a lot of stories

00:16:48.020 --> 00:16:49.020
[Guest]: you know like that

00:16:49.020 --> 00:16:51.020
[Guest]: fascinating stories of course

00:16:51.020 --> 00:16:52.020
[Guest]: of the Romas

00:16:52.020 --> 00:16:53.020
[Guest]: of the gypsies in Europe

00:16:53.020 --> 00:16:54.020
[Guest]: and

00:16:54.020 --> 00:16:55.020
[Guest]: now there's genetic evidence

00:16:55.020 --> 00:16:56.020
[Guest]: which suggests that they

00:16:56.020 --> 00:16:57.020
[Guest]: sort of went out of

00:16:57.020 --> 00:16:58.020
[Guest]: Northwest India

00:16:58.020 --> 00:16:59.020
[Guest]: but interestingly

00:16:59.020 --> 00:17:00.020
[Guest]: they were just not

00:17:00.020 --> 00:17:01.020
[Guest]: you know

00:17:01.020 --> 00:17:02.020
[Guest]: Northwest Punjabis so to speak

00:17:02.020 --> 00:17:03.020
[Guest]: but they belong to the

00:17:03.020 --> 00:17:04.020
[Guest]: low-ranking castes

00:17:04.020 --> 00:17:06.020
[Guest]: so the genetic studies map out

00:17:06.020 --> 00:17:08.020
[Guest]: very closely with

00:17:08.020 --> 00:17:09.020
[Guest]: particular castes

00:17:09.020 --> 00:17:10.020
[Guest]: and them

00:17:10.020 --> 00:17:11.020
[Guest]: so it's very interesting

00:17:11.020 --> 00:17:12.020
[Guest]: as to how

00:17:12.020 --> 00:17:13.020
[Guest]: different social groups

00:17:13.020 --> 00:17:14.020
[Guest]: have had different sort of

00:17:14.020 --> 00:17:15.020
[Guest]: types of

00:17:15.020 --> 00:17:16.020
[Guest]: patterns of mobility

00:17:16.020 --> 00:17:17.020
[Guest]: throughout history

00:17:17.020 --> 00:17:18.020
[Guest]: and that's an important theme

00:17:18.020 --> 00:17:19.020
[Guest]: of this book

00:17:19.020 --> 00:17:20.020
[Amit Varma]: trajectories

00:17:20.020 --> 00:17:21.020
[Amit Varma]: and you know

00:17:21.020 --> 00:17:22.020
[Amit Varma]: you write elsewhere in your book

00:17:22.020 --> 00:17:23.020
[Amit Varma]: that migration

00:17:23.020 --> 00:17:24.020
[Amit Varma]: is one way

00:17:24.020 --> 00:17:25.020
[Amit Varma]: of resistance

00:17:25.020 --> 00:17:26.020
[Amit Varma]: against oppression

00:17:26.020 --> 00:17:27.020
[Amit Varma]: you know

00:17:27.020 --> 00:17:28.020
[Amit Varma]: it's like the political scientist

00:17:28.020 --> 00:17:29.020
[Amit Varma]: Theo Hirschman said

00:17:29.020 --> 00:17:30.020
[Amit Varma]: that if you don't like

00:17:30.020 --> 00:17:31.020
[Amit Varma]: the regime you're in

00:17:31.020 --> 00:17:32.020
[Amit Varma]: you can either

00:17:32.020 --> 00:17:33.020
[Amit Varma]: leave, complain or comply

00:17:33.020 --> 00:17:34.020
[Amit Varma]: and

00:17:34.020 --> 00:17:35.020
[Amit Varma]: migration is a common way

00:17:35.020 --> 00:17:36.020
[Amit Varma]: people just leave

00:17:36.020 --> 00:17:37.020
[Amit Varma]: and

00:17:37.020 --> 00:17:38.020
[Amit Varma]: you know

00:17:38.020 --> 00:17:39.020
[Amit Varma]: one maybe doesn't know

00:17:39.020 --> 00:17:40.020
[Amit Varma]: the historical circumstances

00:17:40.020 --> 00:17:41.020
[Amit Varma]: but the fact that

