[Amit Varma]: kinds

00:20:32.020 --> 00:20:33.020
[Amit Varma]: of

00:20:33.020 --> 00:20:34.020
[Amit Varma]: migrations

00:20:34.020 --> 00:20:35.020
[Amit Varma]: they were

00:20:35.020 --> 00:20:36.020
[Amit Varma]: choosing

00:20:36.020 --> 00:20:37.020
[Amit Varma]: it in

00:20:37.020 --> 00:20:38.020
[Amit Varma]: contrast

00:20:38.020 --> 00:20:39.020
[Amit Varma]: to

00:20:39.020 --> 00:20:40.020
[Amit Varma]: something

00:20:40.020 --> 00:20:41.020
[Amit Varma]: even

00:20:41.020 --> 00:20:42.020
[Guest]: worse

00:20:42.020 --> 00:20:43.020
[Guest]: you do

00:20:43.020 --> 00:20:44.020
[Guest]: have

00:20:44.020 --> 00:20:45.020
[Guest]: lots

00:20:45.020 --> 00:20:50.460
[Guest]: that Delhi becomes a major power center. But most importantly, for the first time Delhi is connected

00:20:50.460 --> 00:20:55.020
[Guest]: to both figuratively, you know, the East Coast and the West Coast. So this opens tremendous

00:20:55.020 --> 00:21:00.300
[Guest]: opportunities of maritime trade, merging with inland trade. So till then it was always separate.

00:21:01.180 --> 00:21:07.420
[Guest]: You also had urbanization in the sense a lot of large cities coming up of Delhi, but also by the

00:21:07.420 --> 00:21:11.660
[Guest]: end of the period Surat and so on, as a result of which a lot of people started moving to these

00:21:11.660 --> 00:21:17.500
[Guest]: places. And finally, there's also pilgrimage networks, which started and you had different

00:21:17.500 --> 00:21:23.180
[Guest]: religious, not maybe faiths, but philosophies. So you have the Sufi wanderers, then you have the

00:21:23.180 --> 00:21:27.740
[Guest]: sort of Vaishnav, Pushti Margi Vaishnavism, which is a new form of philosophical thought,

00:21:27.740 --> 00:21:32.780
[Guest]: which emerges. You have this Sikhism emerges, a religion. And all of these, I argue, actually,

00:21:32.780 --> 00:21:37.500
[Guest]: a lot of these religions had a much more benevolent outlook towards not only trade,

00:21:37.500 --> 00:21:42.060
[Guest]: but also migration. And so they weren't less taboos of sort of moving in many philosophies.

00:21:42.060 --> 00:21:47.260
[Guest]: So arguably, the pace of mobility increased. Note also, there's time of a lot of warfare.

00:21:47.260 --> 00:21:52.620
[Guest]: And so there's what economists would call as a military labor market. And this is different

00:21:52.620 --> 00:21:57.340
[Guest]: because you have full time warriors. But when the size of the army grows, you also need to

00:21:57.340 --> 00:22:01.420
[Guest]: have part time warriors. And so you also have like agriculturalists coming into warfare.

00:22:01.420 --> 00:22:06.700
[Guest]: And many of the dominant, you know, sort of warfare, warrior groups of India, consolidated

00:22:06.700 --> 00:22:10.940
[Guest]: themselves in this period, like the Rajputs and the Marathas, for example. And this is important

00:22:10.940 --> 00:22:15.420
[Guest]: because some of these mobility streams continued well into the recent past, that is, we're talking

00:22:15.420 --> 00:22:20.700
[Guest]: 200 years earlier. So there's some districts of India, which supplied the soldiers, you know,

00:22:20.700 --> 00:22:26.140
[Guest]: in Saran, for example, in Bihar, supplied the soldiers to the Shersa Suri army, then the Mughal

00:22:26.140 --> 00:22:31.500
[Guest]: armies, then the British, the Bengal native infantry, and then much later to the industrial

00:22:31.500 --> 00:22:36.940
[Guest]: sort of mills of Calcutta. So the same region, sending out people, and that becomes a sort of

00:22:36.940 --> 00:22:42.140
[Guest]: pattern for many parts. So the development of a military labor market in this medieval time,

00:22:43.020 --> 00:22:48.460
[Guest]: city building, which became very big, and this integration of inland trade with overland and

00:22:48.460 --> 00:22:53.740
[Guest]: overseas trade. So these sort of three major factors really boosted mobility in a big.

00:22:53.740 --> 00:22:58.220
[Guest]: Note that the speed didn't change much, essentially, for until the advent of the railways,

00:22:58.220 --> 00:23:04.380
[Guest]: the speed of the horse was the constraint. But because of this demand for variety of

00:23:05.020 --> 00:23:07.980
[Guest]: economic sort of needs, mobility increased tremendously.

00:23:07.980 --> 00:23:12.540
[Amit Varma]: No, I find it really intriguing the way you sort of describe the military labor market.

00:23:12.540 --> 00:23:17.340
[Amit Varma]: It's almost like there's a gig economy and you can just turn on an Uber for warriors and figure

00:23:17.340 --> 00:23:21.900
[Amit Varma]: out which is the most profitable war for you to go to. Another thing that struck me is very

00:23:21.900 --> 00:23:27.100
[Amit Varma]: interesting, and I hadn't really thought about it in this way before, was that a lot of the

00:23:27.100 --> 00:23:32.140
[Amit Varma]: urbanization, like you point out in South India was temple generated urbanization, you know,

00:23:32.140 --> 00:23:36.220
[Amit Varma]: benefiting merchants and artisans, whereas typically we today we think of urbanization

00:23:36.220 --> 00:23:40.860
[Amit Varma]: as driven by economic imperatives, you want to form larger economic networks and so on.

00:23:40.860 --> 00:23:47.180
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, religion being a force in both urbanization and migration was really interesting.

00:23:47.180 --> 00:23:56.060
[Amit Varma]: What I also found fascinating was your whole account of slavery. Like, typically, when we

00:23:56.060 --> 00:24:00.220
[Amit Varma]: talk about slavery, we obviously imagine the American South and the Civil War and so on and

00:24:00.220 --> 00:24:06.220
[Amit Varma]: so forth. But India was a market for slaves in both directions. Tell me a bit about that.

00:24:06.860 --> 00:24:11.020
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, slavery has been mentioned since the times of the Arthashastra, maybe even before.

00:24:11.740 --> 00:24:15.980
[Guest]: Different types of slaves, we are accustomed to thinking of slaves usually as men,

00:24:15.980 --> 00:24:20.780
[Guest]: but in Indian history also a lot of accounts of female slavery, whether it's in the Chola Empire,

00:24:20.780 --> 00:24:26.460
[Guest]: the Rajputs, the Mughals. So women slaves have always been there. In this time period,

00:24:26.460 --> 00:24:31.500
[Guest]: for roughly 15 to 18th century, especially when in the US and South America and North America,

00:24:31.500 --> 00:24:36.380
[Guest]: this transatlantic slave trade really began. India really, you know, developed two or three

00:24:36.380 --> 00:24:43.260
[Guest]: major circuits. One was from Africa to India via Arabia. And the most fascinating community,

00:24:43.260 --> 00:24:47.980
[Guest]: which exists till date, is the Siddhi community, who trace the ancestry to this sort of group.

00:24:48.780 --> 00:24:53.020
[Guest]: There's a famous guy called Mallik Ambar, who becomes this big noble in the Ahmednagar dynasty.

00:24:53.660 --> 00:24:57.980
[Guest]: And he comes from Ethiopia to Arabia to what we would call as Maharashtra today.

00:24:57.980 --> 00:25:02.780
[Guest]: And he comes as a slave, and he rises up to be a fairly rich man with a lot of power.

00:25:02.780 --> 00:25:08.220
[Guest]: And Jahangir hates him because he's, you know, thwarting the Mughal attack in the Deccan.

00:25:08.220 --> 00:25:13.020
[Guest]: And his descendants, you know, I mean, the community has a huge setback.

00:25:13.020 --> 00:25:18.060
[Guest]: The slave imports stop after they sort of lose wars. But the community still exists today.

00:25:18.060 --> 00:25:22.700
[Guest]: And so in some parts of the Africa, in Gujarat, for example, even Maharashtra, you'll find

00:25:23.340 --> 00:25:31.180
[Guest]: black skin people of African ethnicity living today. And I work at IIM Ahmedabad,

00:25:31.180 --> 00:25:36.540
[Guest]: and our logo actually comes from the Siddhi Saeed Jali Mosque, which is designed by these artisans

00:25:36.540 --> 00:25:39.820
[Guest]: coming from this community. So I often tell students, actually, that, you know,

00:25:40.860 --> 00:25:45.580
[Guest]: you have to really think twice before selling fair and lovely, because you have, you know,

00:25:45.580 --> 00:25:51.580
[Guest]: the logo of your institute was designed originally by a descendant of a black African slave.

00:25:52.700 --> 00:25:56.060
[Guest]: In terms of slavery on the other side, and this is a less known fact,

00:25:56.780 --> 00:26:03.180
[Guest]: one theory of why the mountains Hindu Kush are called so low is because they were killer of

00:26:03.180 --> 00:26:07.980
[Guest]: Hindus, in the sense, Hindu slaves being taken over the mountains, because of the cold. And so

00:26:07.980 --> 00:26:14.300
[Guest]: there's a huge slave market also of Indians, or people, mainly Hindus, being taken over the Hindu

00:26:14.300 --> 00:26:20.700
[Guest]: Kush to the slave markets of Persia and Central Asia. So there's a circuit from Africa and Arabia

00:26:20.700 --> 00:26:26.700
[Guest]: coming to India, but there's also a circuit from India going into Asia. Again, even in North India,

00:26:26.700 --> 00:26:32.140
[Guest]: slave dynasties existed. So very interesting ways in which slavery existed, of course,

00:26:32.140 --> 00:26:37.260
[Guest]: very harsh. But I would argue compared to the US experience, or the experience of the American

00:26:37.260 --> 00:26:43.260
[Guest]: world, a lot of avenues for upward mobility, which we've still not really found in the American world.

00:26:43.260 --> 00:26:47.980
[Guest]: I think that's a distinctive aspect of slavery in India. Many people have been able to break,

00:26:47.980 --> 00:26:53.580
[Guest]: it was never sacrosanct, you could always sort of rise to the top. If some accident happened,

00:26:53.580 --> 00:26:58.620
[Amit Varma]: like Malaykambar and the slave dynasty with the mission all but but I guess those are the

00:26:58.620 --> 00:27:04.620
[Amit Varma]: slaves that we've imported, but might be slightly harder for slaves that we export to other places.

00:27:04.620 --> 00:27:08.620
[Guest]: Yeah, we don't know enough. Again, this is a slightly mismatch in the records.

00:27:08.620 --> 00:27:12.620
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you in fact, talk about the slogan in Central Asia, when slaves would be taken,

00:27:12.620 --> 00:27:19.260
[Amit Varma]: the slogan being slaves from India, horses from Parthia. Yeah, something you can imagine on the

00:27:19.260 --> 00:27:23.740
[Amit Varma]: side of a medieval billboard. And you also have a mention of in the early 17th century,

00:27:23.740 --> 00:27:29.580
[Amit Varma]: some 18,000 Bengali slaves in two small centres of the Arakan, which is North Burma, which is

00:27:30.460 --> 00:27:37.100
[Amit Varma]: also kind of quite fascinating. And it's the same channel of this Rohingya migration today.

00:27:37.740 --> 00:27:41.260
[Guest]: So it's, it's interesting, because we're talking about three to four centuries back,

00:27:41.980 --> 00:27:47.180
[Guest]: Bengali slaves being taken to Burma. And today we have a reverse sort of an issue of refugee

00:27:47.180 --> 00:27:51.100
[Amit Varma]: trafficking on the other sort of channel. And the Rohingyas are basically the descendants

00:27:51.100 --> 00:27:57.180
[Amit Varma]: of migrants who went from modern day Bangladesh, essentially. And then we sort of come to

00:27:57.180 --> 00:28:01.820
[Amit Varma]: colonialism, which obviously has a bunch of different impacts. But one of the interesting

00:28:01.820 --> 00:28:06.060
[Amit Varma]: things they try to do, which harks back to what you said about, you know, there never really being

00:28:06.060 --> 00:28:11.180
[Amit Varma]: freedom of mobility anywhere, is that they try to cut down on migrating groups like the Banjaras

00:28:11.180 --> 00:28:15.660
[Amit Varma]: and try to make them settle down for reasons of both surveillance and I guess, taxation, because

00:28:15.660 --> 00:28:20.300
[Guest]: a state just wants to be an efficient state. Yeah, I mean, we think of the British, I mean,

00:28:20.300 --> 00:28:24.380
[Guest]: if you ask, you know, did the British increase spatial mobility, or did they fall? But you

00:28:24.380 --> 00:28:27.820
[Guest]: probably think of the railways, the steamboats, and say, obviously, people started moving more,

00:28:27.820 --> 00:28:31.980
[Guest]: which is true. But there are a lot of, again, and this is the thing, some social groups started

00:28:31.980 --> 00:28:36.860
[Guest]: moving more, and some social groups are moving less. And the less ones are people who are sort

00:28:36.860 --> 00:28:40.860
[Guest]: of negatively impacted were precisely those groups who are historically always on the move.

00:28:40.860 --> 00:28:44.140
[Guest]: These are basically the nomadic groups, and the most famous being the Banjaras,

00:28:44.140 --> 00:28:48.540
[Guest]: famous in logistics, all different names in different parts of India. In Hyderabad,

00:28:48.540 --> 00:28:52.220
[Guest]: you have the Banjara Hills, for example, which comes from that. And the Banjaras,

00:28:52.940 --> 00:28:57.740
[Guest]: you know, are really affected, because one, the transport systems are being shifted. So there's

00:28:57.740 --> 00:29:01.660
[Guest]: a technology shock. Two, there's a surveillance shock where they need to be settled down in

00:29:01.660 --> 00:29:07.900
[Guest]: different places. And you can really see sort of, you know, communities getting poorer as a result

00:29:07.900 --> 00:29:12.060
[Guest]: of this. So this is one way in which a lot of communities became richer, thanks to colonial

00:29:12.060 --> 00:29:15.580
[Guest]: rule, but some communities became poor. And definitely the ones which are on the move

00:29:15.580 --> 00:29:20.700
[Guest]: historically, definitely saw a lot of, and they're some of the poorest social groups even today,

00:29:20.700 --> 00:29:24.620
[Guest]: in India. And I was just coming from Dadar, and the other station, the porters,

00:29:25.340 --> 00:29:30.540
[Guest]: even today, they trace the ancestry to this group. And as I sort of write in the book,

00:29:30.540 --> 00:29:35.420
[Guest]: it's sort of slightly ironic, because they were displaced by the railways in the first place.

00:29:35.420 --> 00:29:37.740
[Guest]: And today, they're sort of working on the railways.

00:29:37.740 --> 00:29:41.820
[Amit Varma]: It's going to come full circle. And it's even more ironic, because a lot of the other

00:29:41.820 --> 00:29:46.620
[Amit Varma]: communities and castes which migrate often do it for specific purposes, they go for jobs or

00:29:46.620 --> 00:29:51.820
[Amit Varma]: marriages or whatever. And you could say with people like the Banjaras that the journey was

00:29:51.820 --> 00:29:56.060
[Amit Varma]: the destination they would, you know, it was part of their culture to travel and to have that taken

00:29:56.060 --> 00:30:01.740
[Guest]: away would have been... Yeah, it was deeply traumatic. And that's why many of the revolts

00:30:01.740 --> 00:30:06.540
[Guest]: also started coming from these social groups. Again, we don't know too much about those revolts.

00:30:06.540 --> 00:30:11.180
[Guest]: But on the whole, there's been this mixed effect. You know, definitely some groups,

00:30:11.180 --> 00:30:15.660
[Guest]: especially the coastal India got this massive, positive shock on movement, that is a lot of

00:30:15.660 --> 00:30:20.140
[Guest]: people started to move, because the British connected the whole world in a major way.

00:30:20.140 --> 00:30:23.180
[Guest]: And so this whole overseas migration started in a big way.

00:30:23.740 --> 00:30:28.460
[Amit Varma]: Right. The second chapter of your book is called the Great Indian Migration Wave.

00:30:28.460 --> 00:30:32.780
[Amit Varma]: And what you say about that later is a great Indian migration wave is arguably the largest

00:30:32.780 --> 00:30:38.220
[Amit Varma]: and longest non-coerced migration stream for work in documented history, stop quote.

00:30:38.220 --> 00:30:40.220
[Guest]: Elaborate on that a bit.

00:30:40.220 --> 00:30:43.180
[Guest]: So when we talk migration in Indian history, it's remarkable that

00:30:44.220 --> 00:30:48.940
[Guest]: if you ask the average person, they talk of two migrations. One is the Aryan migration hypothesis

00:30:48.940 --> 00:30:53.420
[Guest]: many thousand years back. And then you come to the 19th century and people talk of indentured

00:30:53.420 --> 00:31:00.300
[Guest]: migration. And that's about it. And my reason of and this is a course of contribution of this book

00:31:01.100 --> 00:31:06.300
[Guest]: is to give a phrase to one of the world's greatest migrations. And these are migrations,

00:31:06.300 --> 00:31:10.060
[Guest]: which are male-dominated as there are three core features, male-dominated,

00:31:10.060 --> 00:31:16.380
[Guest]: remittance-based, semi-permanent. And they're happening pretty much even today. So, you know,

00:31:16.380 --> 00:31:21.020
[Guest]: when you see the Ratnagiri people in Mumbai, most of them do not settle down in Mumbai,

00:31:21.020 --> 00:31:25.580
[Guest]: they go back. And this has been happening since the middle of the 19th century. A lot of my

00:31:25.580 --> 00:31:29.660
[Guest]: research has been to document these regions, which are these regions, go there and find out more.

00:31:30.780 --> 00:31:35.100
[Guest]: It's remarkable, almost the entire West Coast on one side of the Western Ghats,

00:31:35.100 --> 00:31:39.900
[Guest]: from Ratnagiri to Kanyakumari a part of this, a large part of the coastal tracts on Eastern India,

00:31:40.940 --> 00:31:46.700
[Guest]: a whole chunk of Eastern UP, Western Bihar, Uttarakhand, pretty much all of Central India

00:31:46.700 --> 00:31:51.100
[Guest]: and the Deccan is actually out of it. They were not really affected by it. So, this is a story

00:31:51.100 --> 00:31:57.500
[Guest]: of mostly coastal India and the lower Indo-Gangetic belt. And what happened out here is that a lot of

00:31:57.500 --> 00:32:03.340
[Guest]: initial recruitment took place in the colonial era, not necessarily by force. Density was very

00:32:03.340 --> 00:32:09.340
[Guest]: high in these places. But these migrations have now led to a culture of migration, where young

00:32:09.340 --> 00:32:15.820
[Guest]: boys grow up thinking that they will spend their lifetime outside and come back. That's also key.

00:32:16.540 --> 00:32:20.380
[Guest]: And girls grow up knowing that they have to look after the family and land when their husbands are

00:32:20.380 --> 00:32:26.540
[Guest]: away. And it's so strongly rooted in many parts of India. And my sort of estimate suggests that,

00:32:26.540 --> 00:32:31.100
[Guest]: you know, these districts, if you have more than 150 districts out of about 600 districts of India,

00:32:31.100 --> 00:32:36.620
[Guest]: which have this. Another way of saying it is there are regions covering over 200 million people,

00:32:36.620 --> 00:32:41.420
[Guest]: which are completely remittance-based economies, principles of economy runs on money coming from

00:32:41.420 --> 00:32:47.340
[Guest]: outside. And it has been going on since more than 140 years. So, if you compare it with other epochs,

00:32:48.300 --> 00:32:53.260
[Guest]: this actually turns out to be the largest and longest. The largest migration right now is

00:32:53.260 --> 00:32:57.660
[Guest]: the urbanization of China. So, China has, you know, taken hundreds of millions of people

00:32:57.660 --> 00:33:03.180
[Guest]: out from farms to cities. But that's happened in the last 30 years. What's happened in India,

00:33:03.180 --> 00:33:07.420
[Guest]: much smaller compared to Chinese urbanization, but it's been happening for more than 100 years.

00:33:08.140 --> 00:33:14.460
[Guest]: So, the classic indicator for this is the sex ratio. And in India, you know, we typically,

00:33:14.460 --> 00:33:19.820
[Guest]: sex ratios of 800, 900 females to 1000 males in some parts as well. And we're used to this

00:33:19.820 --> 00:33:23.980
[Guest]: phenomenon of the missing women. But Ratnagiri, many districts in India have the phenomenon of

00:33:23.980 --> 00:33:30.860
[Guest]: missing men. And in Ratnagiri, for example, sex ratio has never dipped below 1100 females to 1000

00:33:30.860 --> 00:33:35.980
[Guest]: males. So, it's a female surplus because the men are working outside. In fact, you point out that

00:33:35.980 --> 00:33:41.740
[Amit Varma]: this is not just true at a given point in time, but between 1872 and 2011. That's a heck of a long

00:33:41.740 --> 00:33:48.380
[Guest]: time. It's no census has recorded it till date. And the Ratnagiri, of course, is very extreme,

00:33:48.380 --> 00:33:54.460
[Guest]: but a very similar story, especially if you look at the age group 25 to 40. You'll find it in

00:33:54.460 --> 00:34:00.140
[Guest]: Azamgarh, in UP, in Udupi, in South India, in Sivaganga, in Tamil Nadu. So, virtually every

00:34:00.140 --> 00:34:05.420
[Guest]: state of India has a few districts, which have become these remittance economies. And there's

00:34:05.420 --> 00:34:12.140
[Guest]: very strong networks, which enable these migrations to sustain. In Udupi, in fact, if between 1901 to

00:34:12.140 --> 00:34:19.420
[Amit Varma]: 2011, it never fell below 1090 females per 1000 males. You know, in your chapter, you mentioned

00:34:19.420 --> 00:34:25.900
[Amit Varma]: a number of places and like you mentioned, Saran in Bihar, their sex ratio in 1901 had risen to

00:34:25.900 --> 00:34:32.460
[Guest]: 1200 females per 1000 males. And if you go to the taluks and villages, it's 1400-1500. And so this

00:34:32.460 --> 00:34:36.620
[Guest]: is, it's a massive phenomenon. What are the cultural impacts of something like this?

00:34:37.340 --> 00:34:41.260
[Guest]: You would think that, you know, fertility reduces because the men are away, but that's not the case,

00:34:41.260 --> 00:34:47.180
[Guest]: because as I argue, you just need one good night in order to sort of, you know, get a kid. And

00:34:47.180 --> 00:34:51.420
[Guest]: these migrants do come back. It's not like they're away for years, they come back at least once or

00:34:51.420 --> 00:34:56.860
[Guest]: twice a year. So it's remarkable. As a researcher, I thought fertility would be affected. But clearly,

00:34:56.860 --> 00:35:00.460
[Guest]: you know, Bihar has very high fertility even today. We might think that women would get more

00:35:00.460 --> 00:35:03.980
[Guest]: autonomy, in the sense that the men are away, so they'd have to take more decisions. And that is

00:35:03.980 --> 00:35:09.420
[Guest]: true in some parts of India. But on the whole, not much has changed. What has changed on the

00:35:09.420 --> 00:35:15.260
[Guest]: West Coast, is that with some decent governance, they've been able to use this remittances in a

00:35:15.260 --> 00:35:21.420
[Guest]: smarter way. And you could say that migration has fundamentally transformed this region for the good.

00:35:22.620 --> 00:35:25.500
[Guest]: In Bihar and Eastern UP, however, it's been much, much less.

00:35:26.060 --> 00:35:31.100
[Amit Varma]: And Ratnagiri is a particularly interesting case, because, you know, a common phrase in

00:35:31.100 --> 00:35:34.940
[Amit Varma]: Ratnagiri was, I mean, they looked at Mumbai as something really aspirational, a common phrase

00:35:34.940 --> 00:35:39.900
[Amit Varma]: you've quoted is, Jai Chikholi Techi Mumbai, I hope I'm pronouncing it right. Mumbai belongs to

00:35:40.540 --> 00:35:45.980
[Amit Varma]: those who own a room. And it's very interesting that a lot of the luminaries of Mumbai and indeed

00:35:45.980 --> 00:35:53.100
[Amit Varma]: India are migrants from Ratnagiri. You say here that, you know, 10% of all awardees of the Bharat

00:35:53.100 --> 00:35:58.140
[Amit Varma]: Ratna have been given to people directly or indirectly associated with mass migration from

00:35:58.140 --> 00:36:01.660
[Amit Varma]: this region, like I assume, the Mangeshkars and so on.

00:36:01.660 --> 00:36:08.140
[Guest]: Absolutely. It's a remarkable region. You know, I mean, it's, we remember,

00:36:08.140 --> 00:36:11.740
[Guest]: as I say, Ratnagiri is famous for mangoes, but it's also famous for man goes, you know,

00:36:11.740 --> 00:36:18.140
[Guest]: so it's this massive migration effect. Its contribution has really been truly been outsized.

00:36:18.140 --> 00:36:22.700
[Guest]: But I mean, Ratnagiri, of course, is the Konkan is one region, but of course,

00:36:22.700 --> 00:36:28.780
[Guest]: the many other regions of India who have also exported. And it, for example, the Udupi cluster,

00:36:28.780 --> 00:36:32.700
[Guest]: you know, all the South Indian restaurants that you see across India, most of them are actually

00:36:32.700 --> 00:36:38.300
[Guest]: run by the Udupi guys. And it's a remarkable story of how a guy goes, learns the sort of tricks of

00:36:38.300 --> 00:36:41.820
[Guest]: the trade, and then starts a new restaurant. And it's just like this, literally like a

00:36:41.820 --> 00:36:47.820
[Guest]: McDonald's franchisee model, but very indigenous, many years before McDonald's, and really spread

00:36:47.820 --> 00:36:50.700
[Amit Varma]: its sort of tentacles across. And part of it is almost happenstance,

00:36:50.700 --> 00:36:54.540
[Amit Varma]: isn't it? Because you mentioned that there was a flood in the region in 1923.

00:36:54.540 --> 00:37:00.300
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of people were forced to migrate because of that. And this turned out to be a natural

00:37:00.300 --> 00:37:05.340
[Guest]: Often you have one starting shock, which starts pushing out. More recently, the diamond industry

00:37:05.340 --> 00:37:09.020
[Guest]: got this massive shock in the 1980s. That's why a lot of the Saurashtra Patels got into this

00:37:09.020 --> 00:37:16.540
[Guest]: business. More recently, just, you know, a lot of Bengalis are now in the sort of gold business,

00:37:16.540 --> 00:37:21.900
[Guest]: like this goldsmith kind of business. And from literally Kochi, in the south to Surat,

00:37:21.900 --> 00:37:26.220
[Guest]: most small towns and cities, these are a particular sort of Bengali community,

00:37:26.220 --> 00:37:30.860
[Guest]: which is managing. And again, they had a massive sort of natural calamity in the 80s,

00:37:30.860 --> 00:37:34.300
[Guest]: because of which many people went out. Many of these other regions also, there were a lot of

00:37:34.300 --> 00:37:38.780
[Guest]: famines in the late 19th century. But it's almost all of India is affected by famines.

00:37:38.780 --> 00:37:43.500
[Guest]: So it's not just the fact that there was something bad. There's a negative shock.

00:37:43.500 --> 00:37:48.540
[Guest]: But at the same time, like you said, happenstance, where they find an opportunity. And that is the

00:37:48.540 --> 00:37:53.180
[Guest]: combination which clicks. So while famines affected pretty much all of India, it's the

00:37:53.180 --> 00:37:59.260
[Guest]: coastal areas, where they had the opportunity to go to Burma, Malaysia, Sri Lanka, or anywhere to

00:37:59.260 --> 00:38:03.580
[Guest]: work, that they found this safety valve, where they realized that if there's a famine, they could

00:38:03.580 --> 00:38:07.420
[Guest]: always go there. Whereas much of Deccan India, though there was famine, they tried to move,

00:38:07.420 --> 00:38:12.620
[Guest]: but they couldn't, you know, get an opportunity to latch on to. And as a result of which,

00:38:12.620 --> 00:38:17.260
[Guest]: even though they had negative shocks, they didn't sort of cultivate these migrations,

00:38:17.260 --> 00:38:22.380
[Guest]: cultivate these migration networks, so much. Today, of course, some parts of the Deccan are

00:38:22.380 --> 00:38:26.460
[Guest]: into migration streams, northern Karnataka, for example, and some parts of Maharashtra.

00:38:27.340 --> 00:38:31.420
[Amit Varma]: There's something you wrote about Udupi, which kind of brings me to a larger question. What you

00:38:31.420 --> 00:38:36.540
[Amit Varma]: wrote was, quote, migration from Udupi was unique in that it involved a considerable number of child

00:38:36.540 --> 00:38:41.740
[Amit Varma]: migrants in search of work in the key destination, the restaurant provided free food and

00:38:41.740 --> 00:38:44.940
[Amit Varma]: accommodation, stop quote. And my question really isn't about the child migrants,

00:38:44.940 --> 00:38:49.580
[Amit Varma]: but that's an interesting thing in itself. But it's about how a common thread through all the

00:38:49.580 --> 00:38:54.380
[Amit Varma]: communities and peoples that you describe in this, whether it's the Parsis, or the Sindhis,

00:38:54.380 --> 00:38:59.100
[Amit Varma]: or the Marwaris, or the Gujaratis, all of whom we'll talk about later in this episode, but

00:38:59.100 --> 00:39:03.740
[Amit Varma]: a common thread to all of them is the force of community as a force multiplier,

00:39:03.740 --> 00:39:09.580
[Amit Varma]: so that if you want a better life, you just see where your community has gone. And you can be

00:39:09.580 --> 00:39:14.540
[Amit Varma]: guaranteed that you'll go there and you'll either get a place to work and learn the trade as in the

00:39:14.540 --> 00:39:19.900
[Amit Varma]: case of an Udupi restaurant, or in the case of say Marwaris or Gujaratis, you might even get

00:39:20.460 --> 00:39:25.260
[Amit Varma]: funding from those community networks. And what therefore happens is that number one communities

00:39:25.260 --> 00:39:32.540
[Amit Varma]: tend to specialize in certain kinds of trades, or vocations. And this almost then seems to have,

00:39:33.100 --> 00:39:37.500
[Amit Varma]: in a way, a ghettoization effect, like I was chatting with a friend who was brought up in

00:39:37.500 --> 00:39:42.940
[Amit Varma]: Surat on the show, in fact, I did an episode with Aakar Patel on Hindutva. And Aakar was brought up

00:39:42.940 --> 00:39:47.820
[Amit Varma]: in Surat. And while he was describing Surat, we realized that Surat was both simultaneously

00:39:47.820 --> 00:39:53.820
[Amit Varma]: globalized and ghettoized, that you had communities from across the world kind of gathering there to

00:39:53.820 --> 00:39:58.140
[Amit Varma]: trade and to intermingle, but they were also deeply ghettoized. And it seems that that

00:39:58.140 --> 00:40:04.060
[Amit Varma]: ghettoization or the strengthening of those community bonds is almost inevitable. It is

00:40:04.060 --> 00:40:10.060
[Amit Varma]: as much a feature as a bug, because that's what makes it happen. How do you see the two sides of

00:40:10.060 --> 00:40:14.620
[Guest]: this and the trade offs involved? I think the reason why communities are still so close knit

00:40:15.420 --> 00:40:20.140
[Guest]: is because it sustains itself through marriage. And so the number one reason

00:40:20.700 --> 00:40:26.780
[Guest]: is marriage rules. It's also linked with the age at marriage. Even today, Indian women,

00:40:26.780 --> 00:40:32.620
[Guest]: for its sort of per capita income, marry at an extremely young age. We say, you know, 18 is a

00:40:32.620 --> 00:40:37.660
[Guest]: legal age for women to marry. But when you look at surveys, the median age for marriages among

00:40:37.660 --> 00:40:44.220
[Guest]: women today is 18, which means half the population of India today, even today, women marry below 18.

00:40:45.260 --> 00:40:51.100
[Guest]: And this is the way community has its grip, you know, because if you can control marriage,

00:40:51.100 --> 00:40:55.740
[Guest]: and if you can control marriage within your community, that's how it remains close knit.

00:40:55.740 --> 00:41:00.220
[Guest]: The minute sort of women, for example, can work till 25, 30, and then choose their own partners,

00:41:00.860 --> 00:41:05.500
[Guest]: if that freedom is given, then this community network breaks down. So that's the big trade

00:41:05.500 --> 00:41:09.980
[Guest]: off. And I would, of course, argue that, you know, women should be working or should be getting

00:41:09.980 --> 00:41:16.460
[Guest]: married by much sort of later age groups, and so on. Of course, the strange part about this is that,

00:41:16.460 --> 00:41:21.820
[Guest]: as you said, communities work as major agents of subsidies. They subsidize accommodation,

00:41:21.820 --> 00:41:25.340
[Guest]: food, networks, especially if you're going. And so what's interesting is some of the

00:41:25.900 --> 00:41:30.940
[Guest]: social groups which have been not in business, or not in sort of the, you know, money making

00:41:30.940 --> 00:41:36.540
[Guest]: activities, the way they've stormed these things is using the network, and using the community.

00:41:36.540 --> 00:41:42.220
[Guest]: And so you'll see this in the Sarashtra Patel's move from farming to business, the Gounders in

00:41:42.220 --> 00:41:48.540
[Guest]: South India from again, farming to business. And now slowly, some sort of what people are calling

00:41:48.540 --> 00:41:52.860
[Guest]: as Dalit capitalism, where Dalits themselves are using the networks. And so when you have some

00:41:52.860 --> 00:41:58.140
[Guest]: a body like the Dalit, you know, DICI, which is a Dalit industry in Chambers Commerce of India,

00:41:58.140 --> 00:42:03.740
[Guest]: it's basically a front just as you would have a Marwadi Samaj, for example. So they've realized

00:42:03.740 --> 00:42:08.220
[Guest]: the power of the community. And so what's interesting to me is that everyone now in

00:42:08.220 --> 00:42:10.540
[Guest]: India is trying to come up through a community ladder.

00:42:11.260 --> 00:42:15.740
[Amit Varma]: Which is great. But historically, as you point out, at various points in your book, it's much

00:42:15.740 --> 00:42:19.660
[Amit Varma]: harder for someone from a lower caste to really come up because there are barriers to entry. For

00:42:19.660 --> 00:42:23.420
[Amit Varma]: example, if you want to be in the diamond trade, you basically got to be one of the Palanpur

00:42:23.420 --> 00:42:29.660
[Amit Varma]: regions, and so on. So what you have is that, you know, the trade at the Marwadi's control,

00:42:29.660 --> 00:42:33.740
[Amit Varma]: or the trade at the Gujarati's control, or, you know, across those, they almost have a

00:42:33.740 --> 00:42:38.380
[Amit Varma]: stranglehold on it, where it's very easy for someone from their community to get a step up

00:42:38.380 --> 00:42:43.820
[Amit Varma]: and become prominent. But that kind of upward mobility within that specific trade is much

00:42:43.820 --> 00:42:49.500
[Amit Varma]: harder for somebody from the outside. And as you correctly point out that one reason why the lower

00:42:49.500 --> 00:42:56.300
[Amit Varma]: castes both migrated less and benefited less from migration is because they didn't have access to

00:42:56.300 --> 00:43:00.220
[Amit Varma]: these networks. I mean, it's a good thing that they're now getting built up. And it's also a

00:43:00.220 --> 00:43:04.860
[Amit Varma]: good thing that barriers to entry are sort of less than they were across professions.

00:43:04.860 --> 00:43:07.900
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, this is a wonderful book by Devesh Kapoor and others called, I think,

00:43:07.900 --> 00:43:12.380
[Guest]: Define the Odds. It's basically a profile on Dalit entrepreneurs. And what they find, you know,

00:43:12.380 --> 00:43:16.700
[Guest]: it's remarkable that when they look at commonalities of success, even more than

00:43:16.700 --> 00:43:22.780
[Guest]: reservations or the factors, it's actually migration, the ability to go out to develop

00:43:22.780 --> 00:43:29.340
[Guest]: new networks, and about the ability to fail, but be anonymous, which means that if you fail,

00:43:29.340 --> 00:43:33.820
[Guest]: oftentimes you start something different, and you fail and immediately a community says, you know,

00:43:33.820 --> 00:43:39.100
[Guest]: you're not really born to do this. There's a huge psychological setups of what you can and cannot

00:43:39.100 --> 00:43:43.100
[Guest]: do. And migration is remarkable, because it puts you in settings in which nobody knows you,

00:43:43.100 --> 00:43:47.580
[Guest]: and in situations where you can fail. And I think that's really the power of migration. I know

00:43:47.580 --> 00:43:52.140
[Guest]: better person than Ambedkar, who really realized this power. And that's why Ambedkar was a huge

00:43:52.140 --> 00:43:57.020
[Guest]: champion of migration. It helped him in his personal life. And you know, he advocated. And

00:43:57.020 --> 00:44:01.980
[Guest]: so if you see in Dalit activist circles today, historically, these mottos of educate, agitate,

00:44:01.980 --> 00:44:08.300
[Guest]: and so on, today migrate is also, you know, coming into that timeline. And interesting

00:44:08.300 --> 00:44:13.260
[Guest]: international migration. So a lot of it is now, okay, now we need to go abroad and cross the

00:44:13.260 --> 00:44:18.220
[Amit Varma]: Kalapani and sort of, you know, reclaim the space.

00:44:18.220 --> 00:44:22.300
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you point to three recent memoirs, which also underscore this Narendra Jadhav's

