[Amit Varma]: your show. Welcome back to the Scene in the Unseen. I'm chatting with Chinmay Tumbe about his

00:46:43.660 --> 00:46:48.380
[Amit Varma]: very fine book, India Moving, A History of Migration. You know, before the break, we were

00:46:48.380 --> 00:46:53.580
[Amit Varma]: discussing various sort of communities where the female to male ratio has gone out of whack and

00:46:53.580 --> 00:46:57.580
[Amit Varma]: there are missing men because men cannot leave. And, and the interesting thing is, as I was going

00:46:57.580 --> 00:47:03.180
[Amit Varma]: through the list of these communities, is that they're all sort of migrating from different

00:47:03.180 --> 00:47:09.100
[Amit Varma]: social circumstances for different reasons. Like, you know, the whole Ratnagiri and going to Mumbai

00:47:09.100 --> 00:47:15.020
[Amit Varma]: or Bombay as it then was is one thing with Udupi, it's kind of the restaurant trade, perhaps help

00:47:15.020 --> 00:47:19.260
[Amit Varma]: along by the happenstance of a cyclone and other events which come together and then they're

00:47:19.260 --> 00:47:23.420
[Amit Varma]: completely, the flood, sorry, and they're completely dominating that. And then there's

00:47:23.420 --> 00:47:27.740
[Amit Varma]: Saran in Bihar, which is really interesting, where the sex ratio, in fact, at one point,

00:47:27.740 --> 00:47:31.100
[Amit Varma]: rose to 1200 females with 1000 males. Tell me a little bit about that.

00:47:31.100 --> 00:47:35.180
[Guest]: Yeah, so Saran, as I said, it has this really long history, starting many centuries ago,

00:47:35.180 --> 00:47:38.460
[Guest]: and Saran is one of the few districts of India, we can trace the migration history,

00:47:38.460 --> 00:47:42.620
[Guest]: because the three different historians who wrote about its migration for three separate centuries.

00:47:43.660 --> 00:47:49.020
[Guest]: The first people in Singapore, for example, from the British side was the Bengal native infantry,

00:47:49.020 --> 00:47:54.460
[Guest]: and these were soldiers recruited from Saran. And so in the 19th century, some of the major sort of

00:47:54.460 --> 00:47:59.340
[Guest]: infantry stock was coming from Saran. And as British rule sort of consolidated, so actually

00:47:59.340 --> 00:48:03.500
[Guest]: the demand for army personnel sort of started reducing. In fact, if you compare the Mughal

00:48:03.500 --> 00:48:07.100
[Guest]: army and the British army, the British army is very thin. And so this whole military labor market,

00:48:07.100 --> 00:48:11.340
[Guest]: which had developed was beginning to collapse, which means people who are on the move historically

00:48:11.340 --> 00:48:16.300
[Guest]: had to find new vacations. And so people from Saran actually got hold of the jute mills in

00:48:16.300 --> 00:48:20.700
[Guest]: Calcutta. And so they became just like Ratnagiri labor fueled the cotton textile industries of

00:48:20.700 --> 00:48:25.340
[Guest]: Bombay. It was Saran labor, which sort of got hold of the jute industries. And one company, for

00:48:25.340 --> 00:48:30.940
[Guest]: example, Saran labor from across the 20th century, I think it went from being about one fourth to

00:48:30.940 --> 00:48:36.460
[Guest]: three fourths of the workforce. So again, a very strong network built between Saran and Calcutta.

00:48:36.460 --> 00:48:41.420
[Guest]: The fourth district I talk about is Ganjam in Orissa. And I call it cyclone psychology,

00:48:41.420 --> 00:48:46.380
[Guest]: because Ganjam is a very unfortunate geography. All cyclones tend to end up, you know,

00:48:46.380 --> 00:48:52.140
[Guest]: battering Ganjam. It's faced some sort of a super cyclone once in 15 years. And so 100 years back,

00:48:52.140 --> 00:48:57.980
[Guest]: they were going to Burma. Today, they go to Surat, Gujarat, work in a variety of, you know,

00:48:57.980 --> 00:49:02.300
[Guest]: urban sectors. In Surat, it's the synthetic textiles and so on. But it's a culture which

00:49:02.940 --> 00:49:09.260
[Guest]: kind of has come to the conclusion that if we just focus on agriculture, it's very risky,

00:49:09.260 --> 00:49:13.580
[Guest]: because the super cyclone is going to come once in 10-15 years. And so migration,

00:49:13.580 --> 00:49:18.780
[Guest]: relatively, is a very stable livelihood strategy. It can be harsh, it can be exploitative,

00:49:18.780 --> 00:49:23.740
[Guest]: it has all the social costs of separation, loneliness. But given the realities of climate,

00:49:24.380 --> 00:49:29.740
[Guest]: it's a very safe and I would say smart strategy that they've sort of developed over the last

00:49:29.740 --> 00:49:34.460
[Guest]: 100 years. And in all these places, they have the money orders, they have the migration songs,

00:49:34.460 --> 00:49:39.900
[Guest]: the folk songs. So this is a huge sort of, it's very similar. I mean, if you go to Ratnagiri,

00:49:39.900 --> 00:49:44.300
[Guest]: if you go to Ganjam, if you go to Udupi, if you go to Saran, differences in development,

00:49:44.860 --> 00:49:49.260
[Guest]: but that migration culture that you'll find that the kind of conversations are happening,

00:49:49.260 --> 00:49:54.300
[Amit Varma]: it's remarkably similar. And in fact, you give an interesting statistic here that the number of

00:49:54.300 --> 00:50:00.540
[Amit Varma]: migrants from Ganjam to Surat are more than a lakh, more than 100,000. And that's interesting.

00:50:00.540 --> 00:50:05.420
[Amit Varma]: And the point you make elsewhere in the book is that it might seem strange or counterintuitive

00:50:05.420 --> 00:50:10.540
[Amit Varma]: that if you are, say, in a village in Odisha or wherever, you don't go to the nearest town or the

00:50:10.540 --> 00:50:14.860
[Amit Varma]: nearest city, you go all the way to Surat. But the reason is that's where your community is. So in a

00:50:14.860 --> 00:50:19.020
[Amit Varma]: different sense, you know, with a different kind of geography in mind, that is actually the place

00:50:19.020 --> 00:50:22.540
[Guest]: closest to you. Absolutely. I mean, if you're in Bombay, you might think that, you know,

00:50:22.540 --> 00:50:27.100
[Guest]: Madhya Pradesh is closer to Bombay than Uttar Pradesh. You might think that many more people

00:50:27.100 --> 00:50:31.180
[Guest]: from Madhya Pradesh should be in Bombay than Uttar Pradesh. That's completely the reverse. UP is

00:50:31.180 --> 00:50:37.020
[Guest]: further, but we have more. And that's because once a network starts, it is so strong because it helps

00:50:37.020 --> 00:50:42.380
[Guest]: you find jobs, it helps you find accommodation, above all, information. Migration is all about

00:50:42.380 --> 00:50:46.460
[Guest]: information. What information do you know about the destination place? How safe is that place?

00:50:47.260 --> 00:50:51.580
[Guest]: A lot of you'll see a lot of migrant families diversifying nowadays. Same household, three sons,

00:50:51.580 --> 00:50:55.580
[Guest]: two daughters, or three sons will go to three different cities. And so from a household

00:50:55.580 --> 00:50:58.700
[Guest]: perspective, it's also like a, you know, it's like a portfolio diversification.

00:50:58.700 --> 00:51:04.620
[Amit Varma]: You're hedging your bets. And not just sort of these places, but it's almost you talk about

00:51:04.620 --> 00:51:08.140
[Amit Varma]: our cluster, there are these clusters and corridors all along the coast on either side,

00:51:08.140 --> 00:51:13.500
[Amit Varma]: all the way down, and then all the way around the coast and back up again. And I particularly

00:51:13.500 --> 00:51:17.820
[Amit Varma]: found it interesting that Goa, which is where everyone wants to go, is where there was a lot

00:51:17.820 --> 00:51:21.820
[Guest]: of out migration, people wanted to leave Goa. Goa is India's biggest remittance economy for

00:51:21.820 --> 00:51:27.500
[Guest]: a long time until the 1960s. And some taluks even today are remittance economies.

00:51:28.780 --> 00:51:32.780
[Guest]: Not many people know that, you know, most people love to go to Goa,

00:51:32.780 --> 00:51:36.700
[Guest]: but a lot of Goans actually work outside, especially in the merchant navy.

00:51:36.700 --> 00:51:41.180
[Guest]: So when they did this migration survey, they had to actually keep an option, you know, where are

00:51:41.180 --> 00:51:45.100
[Guest]: you outside India, they had to keep an option saying no man's land. And that was that returned

00:51:45.100 --> 00:51:50.380
[Guest]: the most number of sort of responses. There was a Goa migration survey done and they found that

00:51:50.380 --> 00:51:54.700
[Guest]: in taluks like Bardia Salset, about one third of the households were receiving

00:51:54.700 --> 00:51:58.460
[Guest]: money from outside. That's pretty much the same number in Kerala or Ratnagiri,

00:51:58.460 --> 00:52:02.460
[Guest]: that's mass migration, however you define it, where one third of households are receiving money.

00:52:02.460 --> 00:52:05.100
[Guest]: And that's happening in Goa today. And the survey was done about six years back.

00:52:06.460 --> 00:52:11.340
[Guest]: But of course, not all of Goa today. So Goa is today an aberration on the west coast from

00:52:11.340 --> 00:52:17.180
[Guest]: Kanyakumari to Ratnagiri, some parts of Goa. And that's because, of course, a lot of the population

00:52:17.180 --> 00:52:21.500
[Guest]: permanently left after this Portuguese separation to Portugal, Mozambique.

00:52:22.220 --> 00:52:27.980
[Guest]: But a lot of Goans also started developing new things, because it became, it faces massive

00:52:27.980 --> 00:52:32.460
[Guest]: tourism boom. And so a lot of construction activities started happening in Goa, etc.

00:52:32.460 --> 00:52:36.460
[Guest]: Vizag is another place where a lot of people used to leave, they build the port,

00:52:36.460 --> 00:52:39.820
[Guest]: and they start more migration towards Vizag rather than from it.

00:52:40.380 --> 00:52:44.060
[Amit Varma]: In fact, there was a, you know, very nice little tidbit in your book about how

00:52:44.060 --> 00:52:48.700
[Amit Varma]: Goan Catholics became so good at baking, that that's how they got the name Makapau.

00:52:48.700 --> 00:52:54.700
[Guest]: Apparently, that's the, you know, moniker that they got. It's a story, many of these stories,

00:52:54.700 --> 00:53:00.780
[Guest]: it's very hard to verify. But apparently, this is considered to be the source of the word

00:53:00.780 --> 00:53:06.140
[Guest]: Makapau that we use and, you know, in Bandra and Khar, it is full of this particular population.

00:53:06.140 --> 00:53:12.700
[Amit Varma]: Right. And Kerala also has been obviously very famously an area from which there's been a

00:53:12.700 --> 00:53:17.980
[Amit Varma]: lot of out migration. But, you know, we should probably, for listeners who may not be completely

00:53:17.980 --> 00:53:22.220
[Amit Varma]: clear about this, maybe clarify the terms. What's the difference between emigration,

00:53:22.220 --> 00:53:23.660
[Amit Varma]: immigration and migration?

00:53:23.660 --> 00:53:29.100
[Guest]: Yeah, emigration, in today's context is out of country. So people leaving India going outside.

00:53:29.100 --> 00:53:34.780
[Guest]: Immigration is people coming in into India, for example, Nepalese or Bangladeshis coming to India

00:53:34.780 --> 00:53:39.260
[Guest]: or Mexicans going to US, so they're called Mexican immigrants in the US. And we say

00:53:39.260 --> 00:53:44.460
[Guest]: migrants or internal migrants for, you know, people within the country. You might ask who is

00:53:44.460 --> 00:53:50.540
[Guest]: a migrant? In the census, there are two options. You can be a migrant based on the place of birth,

00:53:50.540 --> 00:53:56.540
[Guest]: which means if I'm born in Pune, and I'm living on the day the census officer arrives in Bombay

00:53:56.540 --> 00:54:01.340
[Guest]: for more than six months, six months is the cut off, then I'm a migrant on the base of place of

00:54:01.340 --> 00:54:07.340
[Guest]: birth. But you'll see that suppose I was in Pune, and I moved to Bombay, spent 10 years,

00:54:07.340 --> 00:54:11.740
[Guest]: and I went back to Pune. And if the census officer asked me in Pune, you know, what's

00:54:11.740 --> 00:54:16.940
[Guest]: your place of birth? I say Pune, and I'm in Pune, then I would be not a migrant. So in order to

00:54:16.940 --> 00:54:22.220
[Guest]: capture moves, they ask you a question, what is your last place of residence? And so in that case,

00:54:22.220 --> 00:54:27.340
[Guest]: technically, you should be saying Bombay. As it turns out, there are a lot of biases

00:54:27.340 --> 00:54:32.940
[Guest]: in migration surveys. And Kerala is a classic example. When the census and the National

00:54:32.940 --> 00:54:38.060
[Guest]: Sample Survey asks, you know, question, what is your previous place of residence? Now, we know

00:54:38.060 --> 00:54:44.300
[Guest]: almost a third of the workforce of Kerala has a Gulf connection. But surprisingly, very few people

00:54:44.300 --> 00:54:49.020
[Guest]: answers saying that their last place of residence was the Gulf, because for them home is Kerala.

00:54:49.020 --> 00:54:54.300
[Guest]: As a result, in the census and the National Sample Survey, we find very few, you would conclude that

00:54:54.300 --> 00:54:59.180
[Guest]: there's very little Gulf connection. There's another survey done by a research center there,

00:54:59.180 --> 00:55:03.740
[Guest]: a large sample size, and just a very specific question. Have you gone to the Gulf? And how

00:55:03.740 --> 00:55:07.900
[Guest]: many years you spend there? It turns out one third of the population has a Gulf connection.

00:55:07.900 --> 00:55:11.980
[Guest]: So it matters as to how you ask the question, and how a person relates to a particular place.

00:55:11.980 --> 00:55:17.260
[Amit Varma]: There's a big gulf between this kind of question. Yeah, so Kerala has always again, as you point

00:55:17.260 --> 00:55:22.700
[Amit Varma]: out, you know, been incredibly open to outside influences. You know, their maritime trade has

00:55:22.700 --> 00:55:27.820
[Amit Varma]: been flourishing for a long time. That's probably where Islam and Christianity first came to India

00:55:27.820 --> 00:55:34.620
[Amit Varma]: from. And now they are known for their high rates of out migration. Is it sort of a question of

00:55:34.620 --> 00:55:40.220
[Guest]: cultural openness to? It could be I mean, the fact that they've, you know, had this coastal culture

00:55:40.220 --> 00:55:46.300
[Guest]: for centuries, definitely is part of the story. But this out migration started in a big way,

00:55:46.300 --> 00:55:50.940
[Guest]: partly also because they got, they're one of the most highly educated states of India,

00:55:50.940 --> 00:55:56.540
[Guest]: even the early 20th century, within India, relatively the most educated, and it's a position

00:55:56.540 --> 00:56:02.540
[Guest]: they've had till date. But it's a case of a highly educated state with less job opportunities. And so

00:56:02.540 --> 00:56:07.660
[Guest]: you've seen a lot of educated young people leave Kerala, both men and women, and go all across

00:56:07.660 --> 00:56:12.540
[Guest]: India first. And then in the last 30 years, the Gulf and then US and variety of places.

00:56:13.900 --> 00:56:19.500
[Guest]: Interestingly, the Gulf story starts with Mumbai, the first recruitment offices of the oil companies

00:56:19.500 --> 00:56:23.980
[Guest]: were in Mumbai in the 1930s and 40s. And interestingly, they had some norms as to who

00:56:23.980 --> 00:56:28.860
[Guest]: they could recruit. And so it was the Keralites in Mumbai who got those jobs. And that's how the

00:56:28.860 --> 00:56:33.740
[Guest]: network started. And so from Mumbai, the locus shifted to Kerala. And that's why you have,

00:56:33.740 --> 00:56:38.220
[Guest]: you know, this massive Kerala when the Gulf started booming in the 70s and 80s, when oil

00:56:38.220 --> 00:56:42.860
[Guest]: prices boomed, construction activity started, and this Kerala connection was formed. And so today,

00:56:42.860 --> 00:56:48.620
[Guest]: in popular culture in Kerala, you know, massive, massive migration from Kerala. Of course, now

00:56:48.620 --> 00:56:52.460
[Guest]: there's a lot of migration to Kerala as well, because Kerala is fairly rich, they don't want

00:56:52.460 --> 00:56:57.420
[Guest]: to do the low end jobs. And so you have the curious case of more than 2 million North Indians

00:56:57.420 --> 00:57:01.420
[Guest]: now working in Kerala. And there's just a Malayali movie just released where

00:57:02.220 --> 00:57:06.140
[Guest]: the film sort of breaks into a song. And the song is sung in Bengali.

00:57:06.780 --> 00:57:08.700
[Guest]: Bengali song in a Malayali film.

00:57:09.340 --> 00:57:15.500
[Amit Varma]: That's pretty wild. Later in your chapter on the Great Indian Migration Wave, you sum it up by

00:57:15.500 --> 00:57:20.540
[Amit Varma]: saying, quote, The Great Indian Migration Wave has for the most part been voluntary in nature.

00:57:20.540 --> 00:57:24.700
[Amit Varma]: It represents an adventure, the ability to break out of the family's gaze and yet

00:57:24.700 --> 00:57:29.180
[Amit Varma]: be able to support it, to enjoy the city lights and the company of friends and relatives,

00:57:29.180 --> 00:57:32.940
[Amit Varma]: and finally to return home with the satisfaction of a life well spent,

00:57:32.940 --> 00:57:37.420
[Amit Varma]: at least in the eyes of the others. For many, though, this would not have been the case as

00:57:37.420 --> 00:57:42.460
[Amit Varma]: life would have cruel twists in store, stop quote. And you're obviously referring here to

00:57:42.460 --> 00:57:49.980
[Amit Varma]: indentured labor, which was a significant factor in out migration of Indians all across the world.

00:57:49.980 --> 00:57:54.540
[Guest]: Yeah, in the 19th century, definitely. As I said, it's, some have called it a new form of slavery.

00:57:55.180 --> 00:57:59.820
[Guest]: I don't use that word. I think a lot of people strategically chose indenture as a way to get out.

00:57:59.820 --> 00:58:03.820
[Guest]: But there's no doubt that they were harsh contracts, however you see it. One way to see

00:58:03.820 --> 00:58:09.500
[Guest]: it is when, you know, Gandhi and the national movement, one of the first sticking points for

00:58:09.500 --> 00:58:15.100
[Guest]: them was the indentured migration, and they got it banned, they got it abolished in the 1910s.

00:58:15.100 --> 00:58:19.100
[Guest]: But the interesting thing is when they got indentured as a system abolished, but the

00:58:19.100 --> 00:58:23.500
[Guest]: migration didn't stop. People continue to move, they switch destinations, but they start, they

00:58:23.500 --> 00:58:27.740
[Guest]: continue. So the pressure to migrate was always there. Apart from indenture, of course, it's

00:58:27.740 --> 00:58:33.900
[Guest]: exploitation on a day to day basis, people eviction, you know, insecure sort of land rights,

00:58:33.900 --> 00:58:39.340
[Guest]: as a result of which migrants in India, they lead fairly insecure lives. That is why this

00:58:39.340 --> 00:58:42.940
[Guest]: connection with the home is so important, because they know that they can always fall back

00:58:42.940 --> 00:58:48.380
[Guest]: on something. And so they never really snap the connection with the rural place, even if

00:58:48.380 --> 00:58:54.380
[Guest]: an entire family has moved. For example, my father's side family comes from Udupi. And it's

00:58:54.380 --> 00:58:59.740
[Guest]: the rare Udupi family which actually settled in Mumbai. I mean, of course, there are lots,

00:58:59.740 --> 00:59:04.060
[Guest]: hundreds and thousands of Udupi families which have settled in Mumbai. But I would argue that's

00:59:04.060 --> 00:59:09.900
[Guest]: the minority, most actually go back. And the minute you settle down, the kids get education.

00:59:09.900 --> 00:59:16.380
[Guest]: And over some time generations, the route with Udupi itself snaps. For example, today, I really

00:59:16.380 --> 00:59:20.540
[Guest]: don't go to Udupi, you know, every now and then, but there's a closer connection with previous

00:59:20.540 --> 00:59:25.180
[Amit Varma]: generations. You know, writing of indentured labor, for example, you're right to quote between

00:59:25.180 --> 00:59:31.260
[Amit Varma]: 1831 and 1920, 2 million people were transported across continents through indenture contracts,

00:59:31.260 --> 00:59:35.740
[Amit Varma]: one third towards the Caribbean, one fourth towards Mauritius, a 10 towards South Africa,

00:59:35.740 --> 00:59:40.620
[Amit Varma]: and the rest scattered at numerous islands and regions, including Fiji, Cuba, Peru and Hawaii,

00:59:41.340 --> 00:59:45.980
[Amit Varma]: stop quote. And the interesting thing is that a lot of these places are now, you know, heavily

00:59:45.980 --> 00:59:51.260
[Amit Varma]: populated with Indians, like I think more than half of Mauritians are Indians and, you know,

00:59:51.260 --> 00:59:56.860
[Amit Varma]: in British Guyana, French Guyana, Trinidad and Tobago, they've kind of huge settled down

00:59:57.820 --> 01:00:01.340
[Guest]: everywhere. Even the political, I mean, in Mauritius, for example,

01:00:01.340 --> 01:00:07.740
[Guest]: Ujjpuri is still a language, you know, it's a language alive. Every, you know, Mauritius

01:00:07.740 --> 01:00:13.020
[Guest]: major political leader has had some sort of an Indian ethnic route. And it's not surprising that

01:00:13.020 --> 01:00:16.860
[Guest]: when you come to India, they have to make a stop to Bihar, because most of these migrants to

01:00:16.860 --> 01:00:21.900
[Guest]: Mauritius and the Caribbean, they trace their roots to the Indo-Gangetic plains. V.S. Naipaul

01:00:21.900 --> 01:00:26.940
[Guest]: himself, you know, wrote these books and his heritage also comes from that part of the world.

01:00:26.940 --> 01:00:31.740
[Amit Varma]: And it's kind of ironic that all of these sort of descendants of people who migrated from Bihar and

01:00:32.300 --> 01:00:37.100
[Amit Varma]: so on are now doing much better than their so called, you know, their fifth cousins or the

01:00:37.100 --> 01:00:41.820
[Guest]: sixth cousins or whatever. Yeah, I mean, that's a very good observation. And it is true,

01:00:41.820 --> 01:00:46.780
[Guest]: related to Bihar, but there's a huge diversity. So Mauritius is spectacular. It's got a per capita

01:00:46.780 --> 01:00:51.580
[Guest]: income many, many times India, many, many times Bihar. But there are also places like in the

01:00:51.580 --> 01:00:55.500
[Guest]: Caribbean, which are not that great. There's Guyana, for example, which is still, you know,

01:00:55.500 --> 01:01:01.020
[Guest]: fairly poor. There's Fiji, where Indians have not been treated well, and is also fairly poor.

01:01:01.020 --> 01:01:05.980
[Guest]: So I think the experience has sort of varied. But it would be a mistake to say that, you know,

01:01:05.980 --> 01:01:12.220
[Guest]: hence they made the right choice. I think it's not fair to judge the legacy, but rather the choice

01:01:12.220 --> 01:01:15.500
[Guest]: they made at that particular time. For example, you might even say that, you know, it's good

01:01:15.500 --> 01:01:20.540
[Guest]: slavery happened in the transatlantic world, because the African Americans in the US are

01:01:20.540 --> 01:01:26.380
[Guest]: better off than Africans. But I think that would be a bit harsh on the whole process of slavery.

01:01:27.900 --> 01:01:32.620
[Amit Varma]: No, I mean, the significant thing about that observation, for example, is what it tells you

01:01:32.620 --> 01:01:36.780
[Guest]: is that there's not something inherent in the people, which stops them from developing or

01:01:36.780 --> 01:01:41.580
[Guest]: progress. Given the right institutions, climate, you will flourish. And Indians have been very

01:01:41.580 --> 01:01:46.780
[Amit Varma]: successful abroad. Exactly. Then we come to sort of two of the major impetuses towards

01:01:46.780 --> 01:01:51.420
[Amit Varma]: progress. The first of them being the railways. Tell me a bit about that.

01:01:51.420 --> 01:01:54.940
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, I mean, started in this, you know, city, the first line, 1853,

01:01:54.940 --> 01:02:00.140
[Guest]: completely transformed the speed of transport, completely. Some say it really unified India,

01:02:00.780 --> 01:02:05.900
[Guest]: massive role in migration, because, you know, people started moving. It's on the cover of the

01:02:05.900 --> 01:02:10.700
[Guest]: book as well. I did a lot of my research, interviewing people in the general compartment

01:02:10.700 --> 01:02:16.780
[Guest]: ends, that's pretty much where migrant India moves off trains. So train is a very special symbol of

01:02:16.780 --> 01:02:22.220
[Guest]: migration, India, both voluntary migration on a day to day basis, but also involuntary migration,

01:02:22.220 --> 01:02:26.940
[Guest]: like the partition, where you have these death trains, Khushwant Singh's famous train to Pakistan,

01:02:26.940 --> 01:02:31.740
[Guest]: for example. So from, you know, life, death, and as I like to say, even love, so many people have

01:02:31.740 --> 01:02:37.260
[Guest]: found partners and trains, like my parents who first met in a Bombay local train. So this train

01:02:37.260 --> 01:02:41.900
[Guest]: is just a unique metaphor for various things in Indian life, but especially migration.

01:02:42.460 --> 01:02:45.900
[Amit Varma]: And the second institution, which you describe as a post office.

01:02:45.900 --> 01:02:50.540
[Guest]: Yeah, and I'll give that it's been even more important. You know, travel happened through

01:02:51.260 --> 01:02:55.500
[Guest]: railways, but travel happened before the railways. And even after the railways came,

01:02:55.500 --> 01:03:00.140
[Guest]: most people from Ratnagiri, Kerala were coming to Bombay by steamers. So there was also water

01:03:00.140 --> 01:03:06.060
[Guest]: transport. But the one thing migrant workers used everywhere was the postal money order. And the

01:03:06.060 --> 01:03:11.980
[Guest]: postal money order was remarkable, because it's the first mass financial instrument, which everyone

01:03:11.980 --> 01:03:18.380
[Guest]: could relate to. India had a unique system. In 1884, they realized it was launched in 1880. Four

01:03:18.380 --> 01:03:21.900
[Guest]: years later, they realized that most of the recipients were women, they were not coming to

01:03:21.900 --> 01:03:26.620
[Guest]: the offices to collect the cash. So they changed the system to make it home delivery of cash.

01:03:26.620 --> 01:03:30.620
[Guest]: And as a system, a unique system only in India, which survived until it was shut down,

01:03:30.620 --> 01:03:35.100
[Guest]: the entire system was shut down a few years ago. And so for more than 100 years, you had

01:03:35.100 --> 01:03:40.380
[Guest]: a system of home delivery of cash. And that's why the postman became this symbol in many parts of

01:03:40.380 --> 01:03:45.740
[Guest]: India, of like this Messiah, because he would come, he would undo his bag, and there'd be money,

01:03:45.740 --> 01:03:51.580
[Guest]: there'd be physical cash out there. And so there are songs on this variety of, you know, theatrical

01:03:52.300 --> 01:03:58.140
[Guest]: incidences based on this particular character. And I spent a lot of my time actually digging out

01:03:58.140 --> 01:04:04.300
[Guest]: information, old postal cards on this, because it also shows you that this remittance economy

01:04:04.300 --> 01:04:08.860
[Guest]: in India is not new. It's been there now for more than 100 years in many parts of India.

01:04:08.860 --> 01:04:13.500
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, you point out that, you know, postal money order traffic grew so much that it amounted

01:04:13.500 --> 01:04:19.500
[Amit Varma]: to two to 3% of the gross domestic product between 1900 and the 1960s, which is a heck

01:04:19.500 --> 01:04:24.140
[Amit Varma]: of a lot. And there are young millennials today who will not know what their postman looks like,

01:04:24.140 --> 01:04:26.860
[Amit Varma]: or they will not know what a money order is. Absolutely. Yeah.

01:04:28.460 --> 01:04:31.100
[Guest]: But they will see a Western Union board, which is the proxy for that.

01:04:31.100 --> 01:04:37.660
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. Yeah. Let's talk about gender a bit now. Because, you know, one of the things that is,

01:04:37.660 --> 01:04:41.260
[Amit Varma]: of course, obvious is that many of these regions from which out migration is happening,

01:04:41.260 --> 01:04:45.660
[Amit Varma]: the gender balance is skewed because the women stay at home. And you've spoken a bit about how

01:04:45.660 --> 01:04:51.820
[Amit Varma]: this affects the social and cultural impacts of this. But it is also true that there were a lot

01:04:51.820 --> 01:04:58.460
[Amit Varma]: of women who were sort of migrating and not always for the most welcome reasons. You know, you've got

01:04:58.460 --> 01:05:05.580
[Amit Varma]: a section here on trafficking and female flight and all of that. And there's a very telling quote,

01:05:05.580 --> 01:05:11.020
[Amit Varma]: you know, which seems to indicate how people were forced to because of circumstances,

01:05:11.020 --> 01:05:16.060
[Amit Varma]: look upon the children as resources. And your sentence sort of is, quote, in one official

01:05:16.060 --> 01:05:21.980
[Amit Varma]: record in the late 19th century, a cultivator's girl was made to swap with a prostitutes boy,

01:05:21.980 --> 01:05:27.420
[Amit Varma]: because apparently neither was of any use to their natural parents, top quote, which is very poignant.

01:05:27.420 --> 01:05:31.420
[Guest]: Yeah, absolutely. This book has also been a revelation to me, because in terms of research,

01:05:31.420 --> 01:05:37.420
[Guest]: I found remarkable sort of cases and instances just on which makes you think about, you know,

01:05:37.420 --> 01:05:43.740
[Guest]: how India has been as a society. And we know that India has not really been the best place for women.

01:05:45.900 --> 01:05:49.980
[Guest]: And especially for migration, you know, when we think of harsh forms of migration,

01:05:49.980 --> 01:05:54.060
[Guest]: women have been disproportionately been affected. Prostitution being massive.

01:05:54.060 --> 01:05:58.220
[Guest]: I write in the book, I mean, it's not just Indian women, but European women who were

01:05:58.220 --> 01:06:02.780
[Guest]: trafficked into India, because you had this huge British standing army, almost completely men.

01:06:02.780 --> 01:06:06.380
[Guest]: And, you know, they had their own sexual needs. And so that's why there's this

01:06:06.380 --> 01:06:12.620
[Guest]: importation of white women as required. So the devdasi form, people have said is also

01:06:12.620 --> 01:06:18.300
[Guest]: a very harsh form of servitude. So varieties of, you know, problems related with female migration.

01:06:18.300 --> 01:06:23.900
[Guest]: And even when women are highly educated, when they go to, for example, to the US,

01:06:24.620 --> 01:06:30.300
[Guest]: it's, I argue, a sort of brain drain, where, you know, highly educated going, but you're not getting

01:06:30.300 --> 01:06:35.020
[Guest]: work because you're not allowed to. Because most of the times, it's the men who have the, you know,

01:06:35.020 --> 01:06:41.500
[Guest]: visa, the H1B, and the women have the H4 visa, or the L2. It's very tough to get work,

01:06:41.500 --> 01:06:46.700
[Guest]: because there are laws which restrict you from doing so. And so, as I say,

01:06:46.700 --> 01:06:50.780
[Guest]: they inevitably become these desperate housewives in the US.

01:06:50.780 --> 01:06:56.540
[Amit Varma]: I mean, even in these modern times, you have sort of women bearing the brunt of that.

01:06:56.540 --> 01:07:03.100
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of, you know, move from the migration of labour to the migration of capital. And you

01:07:03.100 --> 01:07:08.940
[Amit Varma]: talk about how that becomes a force for a lot of migration, for example, the Parsis.

01:07:08.940 --> 01:07:12.540
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, there's this famous myth about how the first Parsi merchant comes and the king of

01:07:12.540 --> 01:07:17.580
[Amit Varma]: Gujarat, Jadhi Rana, tells him, why should I let you in? And he asked for a glass of milk,

01:07:17.580 --> 01:07:22.700
[Amit Varma]: and he put some sugar in it to indicate that, you know, they'll assimilate, but not overwhelm.

01:07:22.700 --> 01:07:28.060
[Guest]: Yeah, it's a it's a very nice, you know, quote. And it tells you also how the community has

01:07:28.060 --> 01:07:33.260
[Guest]: gelled very well in India, it still maintains a strong identity, you know, but it's, it's,

01:07:33.260 --> 01:07:38.940
[Guest]: it's a small community, it's dwindling in size. But again, its contributions have been outsized.

01:07:38.940 --> 01:07:43.900
[Guest]: You know, you look at virtually any sector, and Parsis have made just tremendous contributions.

01:07:43.900 --> 01:07:48.780
[Guest]: The one sector in which they've always sort of blasted against was that they'd never contribute

01:07:48.780 --> 01:07:55.100
[Guest]: to the army. And then you have a guy like Sam Manekshaw. So even that has been saturated.

01:07:55.100 --> 01:08:01.180
[Guest]: So tremendously outside. And I think it boils down to a way of sort of a culture of excellence,

01:08:01.180 --> 01:08:06.220
[Guest]: which built into whatever occupation you take at a very young age. And Bombay, of course,

01:08:06.220 --> 01:08:10.860
[Guest]: it helped that they were in Bombay, which most cosmopolitan city of India. And so they got the

01:08:10.860 --> 01:08:15.260
[Guest]: best, you know, exposure to different things that were happening in the city. And so they leverage

01:08:15.260 --> 01:08:19.180
[Guest]: whether it was arts, whether it was business, you know, you have these pioneers in these,

01:08:19.180 --> 01:08:25.340
[Guest]: even women, Parsi women have been trailblazers in law, like Kurnila Swarabji, variety of fields.

01:08:25.340 --> 01:08:30.060
[Guest]: So it is a tremendous community. But we should also not forget that, like many mercantile

01:08:30.060 --> 01:08:35.740
[Guest]: communities, the wealth really started with the opium trade. And, you know, whether it's the

01:08:35.740 --> 01:08:40.540
[Guest]: almost, I mean, this is not just the Parsis, practically every community in China and India

01:08:40.540 --> 01:08:44.540
[Guest]: owed their wealth in the 19th century to the opium trade, which was basically narcotics,

01:08:44.540 --> 01:08:49.340
[Amit Varma]: including the Tata's. Here one could argue everything in a sense is the opium trade.

01:08:49.980 --> 01:08:52.860
[Amit Varma]: Do you think and I'm just thinking aloud here, since you spoke about how

01:08:53.980 --> 01:08:59.340
[Amit Varma]: Parsis tend to, for whatever reasons, strive towards excellence, you know, just as people

01:08:59.340 --> 01:09:04.460
[Amit Varma]: talk of, say, the Protestant work ethic being a factor in how Europe did whatever they did,

01:09:04.460 --> 01:09:09.660
[Amit Varma]: would you say that in many of the communities, which you describe separately, where you talk

01:09:09.660 --> 01:09:15.500
[Amit Varma]: about the Sindhis, Gujaratis, Marwaris, and so on, and the Parsis, that each of them, can you

01:09:15.500 --> 01:09:19.980
[Amit Varma]: pinpoint at the risk of generalizing, but are there sort of these cultural qualities which

01:09:20.780 --> 01:09:25.900
[Amit Varma]: carry through and therefore become a prominent part in the success of later generations? Like

01:09:25.900 --> 01:09:30.540
[Amit Varma]: you could say, okay, the Marwaris are good at trading and doing deals and whatever, all of that.

01:09:30.540 --> 01:09:35.500
[Guest]: Yeah, I'm usually very hesitant to give culturalist explanations to practically everything

01:09:35.500 --> 01:09:39.580
[Guest]: that might reflect the economics training. Economists in general do not like culturalist

01:09:39.580 --> 01:09:44.460
[Guest]: explanations. But there's no doubt that if you look at the Marwaris, for example, risk taking

01:09:44.460 --> 01:09:50.140
[Guest]: appetite, competitiveness, it's tremendous. So there's definitely something in the community,

01:09:50.700 --> 01:09:55.980
[Guest]: which, but I would say it's a network effect. You know, there's some there's, like in migration,

01:09:55.980 --> 01:09:59.580
[Guest]: something starts it and then there's this massive corridor, which gets generated.

01:09:59.580 --> 01:10:03.340
[Guest]: I think it's a very, very similar thing. So it's not got to do with Marwaris per se,

01:10:03.340 --> 01:10:08.060
[Guest]: you might have social groups, completely non-business like, who might be doing the

01:10:08.060 --> 01:10:13.900
[Guest]: same in two decades. But they need that one role model or one, you know, massive star to be born.

01:10:13.900 --> 01:10:18.140
[Guest]: And everyone become like that. And you've seen that you see that in football, where you see

01:10:18.140 --> 01:10:22.140
[Guest]: certain African countries become very good in football, because they see these role models

01:10:22.140 --> 01:10:28.060
[Guest]: performing very well in Europe. And so I would boil it down to some strong early role models.

01:10:28.060 --> 01:10:32.220
[Guest]: And of course, in the world of business, capital matters. And so if capital is retained within a

01:10:32.220 --> 01:10:37.260
[Guest]: community, then everyone sort of, you know, benefits. Yeah. And a lot of people with sort

01:10:37.260 --> 01:10:42.620
[Amit Varma]: of a North Indian bias may not kind of realize that one of the really significant communities

01:10:42.620 --> 01:10:46.940
[Amit Varma]: in this aspect in India, the Chettiyars from Chettinad in South India, at one point,

01:10:46.940 --> 01:10:51.660
[Amit Varma]: you write quote, at the peak of the power in the 1930s, estimates suggest that the Chettiyars had

01:10:51.660 --> 01:10:58.380
[Amit Varma]: 1650 firms in Burma, 1000 each in Malaysia and Singapore, 500 in Sri Lanka, 200 in French in

01:10:58.380 --> 01:11:05.100
[Amit Varma]: Indochina, which is Vietnam, Laos and Cambodia, and 150 in other East Asian regions, stop quote,

01:11:05.100 --> 01:11:10.460
[Amit Varma]: and that's quite mind blowing. And people don't at least, you know, maybe it's my Amit bias,

01:11:10.460 --> 01:11:13.180
[Amit Varma]: but people don't often think of them in these terms.

01:11:13.180 --> 01:11:18.140
[Guest]: Absolutely. I mean, Chettiyars were by far the richest community in India. Again,

01:11:18.140 --> 01:11:22.700
[Guest]: like the Parsis numbering just about 100,000. So it's not a very big community. These firms,

01:11:22.700 --> 01:11:26.460
[Guest]: of course, small firms, but still, as you can imagine, just a sheer number,

01:11:26.460 --> 01:11:30.300
[Guest]: most of them in money lending, but then also in timber, and then start plantations.

01:11:30.940 --> 01:11:36.460
[Guest]: So really a very widespread transnational community at the early 20th century. And it's a

01:11:36.460 --> 01:11:40.140
[Guest]: remarkable case of decline, actually, over the 20th century, because they lose all their money

01:11:40.140 --> 01:11:45.820
[Guest]: in Burma. And sort of they really fall down. But if you go to Chettinad, even today, you'll see

01:11:45.820 --> 01:11:51.900
[Guest]: these houses, like if you go to, you know, parts of, close to Pilani in Rajasthan, where you see

01:11:51.900 --> 01:11:58.060
[Guest]: these Marwadi havelis of old style havelis. In Chettinad, you have these Burmese teakwood houses,

01:11:58.060 --> 01:12:02.860
[Guest]: even today, which is a reminder of this Burmese connection. Even today, there's a Burma

01:12:02.860 --> 01:12:08.780
[Guest]: investors group in of the Chettiyars. And they stake claim to land in Burma even today, they feel

01:12:08.780 --> 01:12:14.300
[Guest]: they were unfairly knocked out of Burma, which they're never going to get, but they've not yet

01:12:14.300 --> 01:12:18.940
[Amit Varma]: lost hope. So, you know, reading about many of these, one of the things that is common between

01:12:18.940 --> 01:12:23.100
[Amit Varma]: these groups that were responsible for the migration of capital, whether it's the Khatri's

01:12:23.100 --> 01:12:28.540
[Amit Varma]: who were money lenders, or whether it's the Marwari's, in fact, in 1844, the Bombay Times and

01:12:28.540 --> 01:12:32.460
[Amit Varma]: Journal of Commerce, which is now the Times of India, for whom I write a column, ran a brief

01:12:32.460 --> 01:12:36.380
[Amit Varma]: piece called Beware of the Marwari's. And I want to quote from that, and the quote is in your book.

01:12:37.100 --> 01:12:41.420
[Amit Varma]: Quote, these Marwari's leave their own country for the purpose of trading and they are spread

01:12:41.420 --> 01:12:47.500
[Amit Varma]: all over Hindustan. A Marwari's shop may be seen as a hamlet, may be seen in a hamlet consisting

01:12:47.500 --> 01:12:52.380
[Amit Varma]: of only four or five cottages. In fact, were you to search all Hindustan, it would be difficult

01:12:52.380 --> 01:12:57.020
[Amit Varma]: to find an agricultural village without a Marwari. When they arrive here, they commence by selling

01:12:57.020 --> 01:13:01.900
[Amit Varma]: gram. And in the course of four or five years, they become opulent bankers. The causes of this

01:13:01.900 --> 01:13:07.260
[Amit Varma]: are they unjust dealings. Therefore, my advice to my countrymen is this, that they avoid entering

01:13:07.260 --> 01:13:13.660
[Amit Varma]: into any transactions of this nature with such deceivers as these. Stop, quote, and fall. My

01:13:13.660 --> 01:13:18.860
[Amit Varma]: Marwari listeners, these are not my words. I was quoting from the Times of India. And this takes

01:13:18.860 --> 01:13:25.260
[Amit Varma]: us back to a sort of this very suspicious outlook towards trade. Again, you quote from the Arthashastra,

01:13:25.260 --> 01:13:32.140
[Amit Varma]: which is, you know, 1800 years old, which also refers to traders as, quote, all thieves in effect,

01:13:32.140 --> 01:13:38.860
[Amit Varma]: if not name. And stop, quote, and then says, quote, they shall be prevented from oppressing

01:13:38.860 --> 01:13:43.580
[Amit Varma]: the people. So a lot of these migrants were fundamentally both traders and moneylenders,

01:13:43.580 --> 01:13:48.300
[Guest]: professions looked upon with suspicion. If you see, you know, after 1991, with this liberalisation,

01:13:48.300 --> 01:13:53.580
[Guest]: economic boom, a lot of people have kind of wrongly concluded that India has always been

01:13:53.580 --> 01:13:57.900
[Guest]: open to trade and so on. And I would argue that yes, but in only a few communities. Actually,

01:13:57.900 --> 01:14:03.340
[Guest]: the default, like the notion of Arthashastra, was this healthy scepticism towards trade,

01:14:03.340 --> 01:14:08.940
[Guest]: you can almost call it like this, you know, a culture where salvation is more important than

01:14:08.940 --> 01:14:14.300
[Guest]: making money. And you find that in many communities even today. And hence, when a lot of communities

01:14:14.300 --> 01:14:18.540
[Guest]: in India started making a lot of serious money in the 19th century, especially the Marwadis,

01:14:18.540 --> 01:14:22.540
[Guest]: there was a lot of opposition. And it's important because today when we see anti-immigrant

01:14:22.540 --> 01:14:27.820
[Guest]: sort of, you know, views and whether it's in the US or UK, or even in India, it's labour migration,

01:14:27.820 --> 01:14:32.380
[Guest]: you know, whether it's in the North East India or US, it's anti-labour migration. But there are

01:14:32.380 --> 01:14:36.940
[Guest]: also cases in history where there's anti-capital migration. And the classic example is Marwadi

01:14:36.940 --> 01:14:43.900
[Guest]: migration in India. And in the Bengali nationalist PCRA called them parasites. The Chettiyars were

01:14:43.900 --> 01:14:49.500
[Guest]: also abused and thrown out. Most famously in East Africa, Idi Amin kicked out, you know,

01:14:49.500 --> 01:14:54.540
[Guest]: kicked out, you know, Indian traders. And what's interesting is, it's not sustainable,

01:14:54.540 --> 01:14:58.460
[Guest]: because in any region, you need some capital to grow with. And so whether it's East Africa,

01:14:58.460 --> 01:15:02.380
[Guest]: who are actually wooing back the Indians who they kicked out 30 years back, they're actually

01:15:02.380 --> 01:15:06.460
[Guest]: wooing them back to Kenya and Uganda today. And in the case of Times of India, of course,

01:15:06.460 --> 01:15:09.580
[Guest]: the ownership, you know, moved on to Marwadi hands 100 years later,

01:15:09.580 --> 01:15:15.340
[Amit Varma]: which is the ultimate revenge, take that bitch. And, you know, speaking of the Gujaratis getting

01:15:15.340 --> 01:15:20.140
[Amit Varma]: kicked out of East Africa, you know, 50,000 partidars get kicked out of East Africa, a bunch

01:15:20.140 --> 01:15:24.940
[Amit Varma]: of them go to the UK. And you've got a very nice anecdote about how, quote, in one local cricket

01:15:24.940 --> 01:15:30.780
[Amit Varma]: match in Bradford in 2001, all 21 players on the field were Patels. The scorekeeper himself,

01:15:30.780 --> 01:15:35.740
[Amit Varma]: a Patel, had the fairly amusing job of recording a scoreboard on the lines of Patel, caught Patel,

01:15:35.740 --> 01:15:42.700
[Amit Varma]: Patel, bowl Patel, Patel, run out Patel, and so on. It's a remarkable cricket match.

01:15:42.700 --> 01:15:49.740
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, let's let's kind of move on to another significant section of your book, which is about

01:15:49.740 --> 01:15:56.620
[Amit Varma]: the diaspora, which is about not the sort of internal migration, but the diasporas that have

01:15:57.500 --> 01:16:03.020
[Amit Varma]: formed. And you say that today, there's a vast Indian diaspora of over 25 million people across

01:16:03.020 --> 01:16:07.020
[Amit Varma]: the world. Tell me a little bit about this, because one of the crucial points you also make

01:16:07.020 --> 01:16:13.420
[Amit Varma]: is that these diasporas reside both within and outside India and the diaspora within India is

01:16:13.420 --> 01:16:16.860
[Guest]: double the size of the international diaspora. Yeah, this is actually not well known. For

01:16:16.860 --> 01:16:20.060
[Guest]: example, the number of people who speak Bengali, there are more people speaking Bengali within

01:16:20.060 --> 01:16:25.180
[Guest]: India, outside Bengali heartland than outside. Like me. Yeah, you wouldn't have thought I was

01:16:25.180 --> 01:16:31.500
[Guest]: Bengali, right? And this is also a surprise for me, except the Malayalis, I think. The Malayalis

01:16:31.500 --> 01:16:35.980
[Guest]: have this massive international diaspora. But it was most Indian linguistic groups have a larger

01:16:35.980 --> 01:16:40.860
[Guest]: internal diaspora. And this is important because often the internal diasporas, firstly, what is a

01:16:40.860 --> 01:16:45.660
[Guest]: diaspora? A diaspora is basically a scattering of a particular, you know, identity, whether it's a

01:16:45.660 --> 01:16:52.860
[Guest]: language or ethnicity, or religion. And if you see the global diaspora is about 25 million,

01:16:52.860 --> 01:16:57.820
[Guest]: internal diaspora, linguistic, I say it's about 60 million. And the internal diaspora is like a

01:16:57.820 --> 01:17:02.060
[Guest]: launchpad for the international diaspora. Often, like we said, you know, the Biharis who are now

01:17:02.060 --> 01:17:07.260
[Guest]: going to the Gulf, are going via Kerala, through networks cultivated in Kerala, the Gujaratis who

01:17:07.260 --> 01:17:12.860
[Guest]: went outside, Bombay was a major launchpad, for example. So this is this matters, you know, these

01:17:12.860 --> 01:17:19.100
[Guest]: these small sort of connections matter. The international diaspora is varied, it's so diverse,

01:17:19.100 --> 01:17:24.060
[Guest]: you have the old diaspora, that you can call it the plantation diaspora. So they were mainly sugar

01:17:24.060 --> 01:17:28.460
[Guest]: plantations. But there's rubber plantations, tea plantations, coffee plantations, and these are the

01:17:28.460 --> 01:17:33.420
[Guest]: guys who went to Mauritius, Fiji, and so on. And in a lot of those countries, Indian ethnic Indians

01:17:33.420 --> 01:17:39.820
[Guest]: now make up more than half the population. The new diaspora can be summarized as a U-turn,

01:17:39.820 --> 01:17:46.060
[Guest]: U meaning three U's. So that's US, UK, UAE. And these three countries specifically, you know,

01:17:46.060 --> 01:17:50.860
[Guest]: today attract a lot of Indians, a lot of investment, a lot of overseas investment,

01:17:50.860 --> 01:17:56.620
[Guest]: a lot of remittances comes from those places. And today, India, you know, earlier, they've also

01:17:56.620 --> 01:18:00.940
[Guest]: concerns of brain drain, and so on. Today, nobody talks so much. And the fundamental reason is India

01:18:00.940 --> 01:18:04.700
[Guest]: is today the world's largest recipient of international remittances, and you get more

01:18:04.700 --> 01:18:12.060
[Guest]: than $70 billion from people outside. It's about two to 3% of India's GDP. I mean, it's a huge part

01:18:12.060 --> 01:18:16.300
[Guest]: of the balance of payments. Without it, India would really be struggling. So we've kind of

01:18:16.300 --> 01:18:19.500
[Guest]: recognized the contribution of migrants from coming from outside. And a lot of this money

01:18:19.500 --> 01:18:24.220
[Guest]: comes from Gulf, which is on, you know, which also has a lot of low skilled labor. A lot of it comes

01:18:24.220 --> 01:18:29.180
[Guest]: from the US, which is at the high skilled labor. Today's diaspora, however, slightly different from

01:18:29.180 --> 01:18:36.620
[Guest]: the old diaspora, because it is much more elite, in the sense the guys who are going out are

01:18:36.620 --> 01:18:41.900
[Guest]: disproportionately drawn from the upper castes. Religion wise, it's different, because in the

01:18:41.900 --> 01:18:46.300
[Guest]: Gulf, there's an over-representation of Muslims, in the US, over-representation of Hindus. But

01:18:46.300 --> 01:18:51.740
[Guest]: caste wise, there's this massive Gulf, which was not the case 100 years back, because it was almost

01:18:51.740 --> 01:18:57.820
[Guest]: like a cross section of an Indian village would be found on a boat going to Fiji. But today,

01:18:57.820 --> 01:19:02.540
[Guest]: when you see the plain, it's not really a cross section of Indian society. So it's much more elite.

01:19:02.540 --> 01:19:07.500
[Guest]: And in the US, like the political scientists, Devish Kapoor and others have called it the other

01:19:07.500 --> 01:19:15.180
[Guest]: 1%. It's really an extremely elite diaspora. So when we say, you know, Indians are so brainy, or

01:19:15.180 --> 01:19:19.900
[Guest]: a classic comment I get is, you know, Indians are very good at mathematics, and they're looking at

01:19:19.900 --> 01:19:27.660
[Amit Varma]: Indians in the US. But this is really the top end. You know, it's not just a selection bias,

01:19:27.660 --> 01:19:35.900
[Amit Varma]: it's what you call the triple selection bias. And which is why Indian Americans outperform every

01:19:35.900 --> 01:19:40.220
[Amit Varma]: subgroup in America in terms of income and education, as you write here. But it's not

01:19:40.220 --> 01:19:44.140
[Amit Varma]: just the three U's, it's also Southeast Asia, which is often ignored, isn't it, when it comes

01:19:44.140 --> 01:19:49.340
[Guest]: to looking at the diaspora? I mean, if you look at the whole arc, Burma, Malaysia, Sri Lanka,

01:19:49.340 --> 01:19:54.380
[Guest]: this was the hub 100 years back. Burma and Sri Lanka have fallen out. But Malaysia, Singapore,

01:19:54.380 --> 01:19:58.940
[Guest]: especially are still very strong. So today, I mean, outside the three U's, Singapore definitely

01:19:58.940 --> 01:20:04.220
[Guest]: is a huge hub for Indians, a lot of Indian entrepreneurs, businessmen. And it's here,

01:20:04.220 --> 01:20:08.700
[Guest]: when you talk of diaspora, inevitably, we start talking about the Sindhis. Because the Sindhis

01:20:08.700 --> 01:20:14.460
[Guest]: are a group which have become so transnational. I mean, virtually every country, Gujaratis and

01:20:14.460 --> 01:20:20.460
[Guest]: Punjabis, I would say, Sindhis, Punjabis, and Gujaratis are most transnational. And then the

01:20:20.460 --> 01:20:25.020
[Guest]: Malayalis and Tamils, of course, Karnataka is to a slightly less extent. What's interesting is

01:20:25.580 --> 01:20:31.820
[Guest]: Bengali diaspora, of course, we add Bangladesh, it's very wide. But the sort of more recent sort

01:20:31.820 --> 01:20:36.460
[Guest]: of migrations have been more internal. That is, you know, from West Bengal to different parts of

01:20:36.460 --> 01:20:42.780
[Guest]: India. But again, what's not changed is that Central India, this whole arc of the Deccan

01:20:42.780 --> 01:20:48.860
[Guest]: Plateau, and Northeast India, like 100 years back, they are really not into this international

01:20:48.860 --> 01:20:53.500
[Guest]: migration in a big way. Why do you think that is? It's again, these historic networks, I would argue

01:20:53.500 --> 01:20:57.900
[Guest]: that. So less opportunity, therefore, basically, more like, yeah, the coasts have had sort of

01:20:57.900 --> 01:21:02.540
[Guest]: starting advantage, because they've had these old ties. And so they've just been synced with it.

01:21:02.540 --> 01:21:07.340
[Guest]: Because remember, the British Empire worked from three ports. Delhi came much later. It was Bombay,

01:21:07.340 --> 01:21:14.060
[Guest]: Chennai, Calcutta. So the coastal sort of India had much wider exposure to trade ideas, movement

01:21:14.620 --> 01:21:19.020
[Guest]: for international sort of connections than the hinterland. So there's this clear bias towards

01:21:19.020 --> 01:21:24.620
[Guest]: the coast rather than the hinterland. In sort of independent India, apart from Delhi, and now much

01:21:24.620 --> 01:21:30.060
[Guest]: more recently, Pune, Hyderabad, Bangalore. But apart from that, there's a huge part in the center,

01:21:30.060 --> 01:21:36.220
[Guest]: which is kind of been sort of ignored. And with migration, you need information. And so it's only

01:21:36.220 --> 01:21:40.380
[Guest]: now that the information is percolating. And so who knows, in maybe 20 years down the line, you'll

01:21:40.380 --> 01:21:45.420
[Amit Varma]: find a lot of migration from these places. In 2006, I traveled through Pakistan, I was covering

01:21:45.420 --> 01:21:49.580
[Amit Varma]: India's cricket tour there. So I was there for a couple of months. And one of the things that sort

01:21:49.580 --> 01:21:56.460
[Amit Varma]: of struck me is that wherever I went, people's sense of community identity was seemed stronger

01:21:56.460 --> 01:22:01.740
[Amit Varma]: to me than their sense of being Pakistani. So for example, with my friends in Lahore,

01:22:01.740 --> 01:22:06.460
[Amit Varma]: it would be the Punjabi identity was really strong, much more than the sense of the idea of

01:22:06.460 --> 01:22:11.020
[Amit Varma]: Pakistan. And at that point, it seemed to me and this was probably a shallow observation, but the

01:22:11.020 --> 01:22:16.380
[Amit Varma]: idea of Pakistan seemed weaker at that level than the idea of India. But reading your book, one thing

01:22:16.380 --> 01:22:21.500
[Amit Varma]: I thought was that, you know, if you look at the histories of these communities, and the way they've

01:22:21.500 --> 01:22:27.260
[Amit Varma]: kind of stuck together through the centuries, and they have these sort of tides, which, you know,

01:22:27.260 --> 01:22:32.220
[Amit Varma]: lift an entire community along, or, you know, you actually have communities, small communities

01:22:32.220 --> 01:22:39.900
[Amit Varma]: getting, you know, displaced en masse, as it were, very often, that it even seems that the idea of

01:22:39.900 --> 01:22:46.060
[Amit Varma]: nation, especially India, which is just over 70 years old, seems relatively nebulous to the idea

01:22:46.060 --> 01:22:51.980
[Amit Varma]: of community. So, you know, much as I absolutely deplore identity politics, for example, I can

01:22:51.980 --> 01:22:59.500
[Amit Varma]: also see why people naturally gravitate towards it. Absolutely. I mean, the central theme of a

01:22:59.500 --> 01:23:07.660
[Guest]: person growing up in India, I mean, is implicitly that, and explicitly that you need to be within

01:23:07.660 --> 01:23:13.660
[Guest]: your fold, right? I mean, that's so strongly ingrained into who you eat with, who you live

01:23:13.660 --> 01:23:19.660
[Guest]: with, spatial segregation, and eventually who you marry with. And these norms, I mean, of course,

01:23:19.660 --> 01:23:25.180
[Guest]: they're breaking down, but very slowly, right? And so, as a result of which, this community logic

01:23:25.180 --> 01:23:29.340
[Guest]: is very strong. Now, Raghuram Rajan has a new book, you know, called The Third Pillar. And he

01:23:29.340 --> 01:23:33.740
[Guest]: argues that one of the reasons for this kind of stuff you're seeing around the world today is that

01:23:34.300 --> 01:23:40.140
[Guest]: between markets and the state, there's also the community, and the community has been ignored.

01:23:40.140 --> 01:23:45.740
[Guest]: And that's, I think that's a very interesting observation that he's making. And maybe in India,

01:23:45.740 --> 01:23:49.740
[Guest]: I would argue that, of course, the communities have always been at the forefront, you know,

01:23:49.740 --> 01:23:54.620
[Guest]: whether it's for reservation or political thing, specific communities have always been able to

01:23:54.620 --> 01:23:59.660
[Guest]: galvanize. And so it's a very core part of the political process now. I mean, you could say that,

01:24:00.620 --> 01:24:03.260
[Guest]: you know, it just simply works on community blocks.

01:24:03.980 --> 01:24:07.020
[Amit Varma]: And then what are the sort of trade offs involved there? Because on one hand,

01:24:07.020 --> 01:24:11.180
[Amit Varma]: the advantage of being part of a community is that you of course, have a sense of belonging,

01:24:11.180 --> 01:24:16.620
[Amit Varma]: and you have a sense of home, not necessarily just in a geographical sense. And you also have

01:24:16.620 --> 01:24:21.260
[Amit Varma]: access to all these networks, and these people will take care of you and so on. But the flip

01:24:21.260 --> 01:24:25.660
[Amit Varma]: side of it is that can also be divisive, though, I mean, I would argue, if you look at India's

01:24:25.660 --> 01:24:30.220
[Amit Varma]: history, it hasn't necessarily been divisive. You have so many communities sort of coexisting

01:24:30.220 --> 01:24:35.340
[Amit Varma]: and intermingling to mutual benefit, but it can be divisive. And especially in these times where

01:24:35.340 --> 01:24:40.620
[Amit Varma]: our politics becomes more and more polarized and divisive. How do you see these sort of trade

01:24:40.620 --> 01:24:45.020
[Guest]: offs playing out? Yeah, it's a very good question. I don't have any clear sort of, you know, answer

01:24:45.020 --> 01:24:49.900
[Guest]: to that. I just feel like my experience has been when you talk to different friends, right? So

01:24:50.540 --> 01:24:55.340
[Guest]: if I talk to friends coming from the Dalit backgrounds, when I talk about community with

01:24:55.340 --> 01:25:01.580
[Guest]: them, the experience is much more of, you know, what are you talking about? This is basically

01:25:01.580 --> 01:25:06.540
[Guest]: exploitation. You can call it caste community for us, it is exploitation. I think one has to be

01:25:06.540 --> 01:25:12.460
[Guest]: very sensitive to that. Whereas you talk with several other groups who have been more privileged.

01:25:13.260 --> 01:25:17.580
[Guest]: And like we discussed, you know, they're often seen as the outsiders, they now have a grouse

01:25:17.580 --> 01:25:22.780
[Guest]: that people are out to get us, right? For example, the Brahmins have this classic grouse that we were

01:25:22.780 --> 01:25:28.860
[Guest]: forced to move because of reservations, you know, there's this huge identity around that. So I think

01:25:29.420 --> 01:25:35.980
[Guest]: these are the sort of different tensions in which each community is facing. Some, which justifiably

01:25:35.980 --> 01:25:41.420
[Guest]: have been exploited for long, and some which now feel that they're being exploited, even though

01:25:41.420 --> 01:25:45.180
[Guest]: there might not be any evidence on that. So in a strange way, every community feels that they're

01:25:45.180 --> 01:25:49.260
[Guest]: being exploited. It's a very unique situation that we are in now.

01:25:49.820 --> 01:25:53.980
[Amit Varma]: And I wonder if, you know, some of these resentments between communities or between

01:25:53.980 --> 01:26:00.220
[Amit Varma]: peoples and so on also comes from a kind of forced migration, which you describe in the second half

01:26:00.220 --> 01:26:06.380
[Amit Varma]: of your book, which is all the displacements which have happened because of partition,

01:26:06.380 --> 01:26:11.980
[Amit Varma]: for example, being a very big reason and not just one partition of 1947. But the multiple

01:26:12.860 --> 01:26:20.060
[Amit Varma]: partitions you sort of point out, you know, the Bangladesh in 71, the Burma just before that,

01:26:20.060 --> 01:26:24.620
[Amit Varma]: and all the displacements, for example, in 1990, the Kashmiri pundits being forced to flee.

01:26:25.340 --> 01:26:29.820
[Amit Varma]: Another striking statistic in your book is about how two thirds of the people in Delhi

01:26:29.820 --> 01:26:32.940
[Amit Varma]: are in some way migrants, especially in 1951.

01:26:33.580 --> 01:26:37.740
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And do you think that lingers on through the generations? Like if you look at some of the

01:26:38.300 --> 01:26:43.820
[Amit Varma]: sort of support for say, Hindutva forces today, would you say that some of it comes from memories

01:26:43.820 --> 01:26:48.620
[Amit Varma]: and resentments, and therefore are not all that hard to understand?

01:26:48.620 --> 01:26:53.340
[Guest]: Absolutely. I mean, if you look at Kashmiri pundits, it's very obvious, you know, where the

01:26:53.340 --> 01:26:59.100
[Guest]: grouse is coming from. It was a painful incident. It was a horrendous incident, this whole Kashmiri

01:26:59.100 --> 01:27:05.740
[Guest]: pundit exodus. But fundamentally, it's the same reasons. It's hyper nationalism in Kashmir at

01:27:05.740 --> 01:27:11.580
[Guest]: that point. It's hyper masculinity, aggression. And unfortunately, this is being repeated now

01:27:11.580 --> 01:27:15.900
[Guest]: in different ways in India. Partition, you're absolutely right. For example,

01:27:15.900 --> 01:27:21.500
[Guest]: the RSS would say that, you know, it is us who actually protected people at that point of time.

01:27:21.500 --> 01:27:25.420
[Guest]: So, you know, a similar thing in Bombay. A lot of people love the Shiv Sena because they say,

01:27:25.420 --> 01:27:29.420
[Guest]: you know, in the 90s, during the riots, it's the Shiv Sena who stood up and protected us.

01:27:29.980 --> 01:27:34.460
[Guest]: And so this becomes a very solid part of the identity building process. And so

01:27:34.460 --> 01:27:39.500
[Guest]: there's a clear connection. I mean, Sindhis, for example, very, very closely aligned with

01:27:39.500 --> 01:27:45.100
[Guest]: hardcore nationalist feelings. There's also the case in the case of Sindhis of trying to prove

01:27:45.100 --> 01:27:52.140
[Guest]: themselves that they are Hindu in a very, very strong way. And so this kind of seems to dominate

01:27:52.140 --> 01:27:55.980
[Guest]: a lot of the logic because a lot of people, because they're often being taunted as being

01:27:55.980 --> 01:28:01.740
[Guest]: coming from the other side. And so in order to sort of dismiss any notion of that, it kind of

01:28:01.740 --> 01:28:05.980
[Guest]: go to the other extreme and say, no, no, no, we are, you know, you need to assert your identity

01:28:05.980 --> 01:28:11.500
[Guest]: even more. So I do think some of it comes apart in that way. I don't know if there's any empirical

01:28:11.500 --> 01:28:17.980
[Guest]: relation, like on average to Sindhis, you know, are they more nationalist than others? I don't

01:28:17.980 --> 01:28:22.940
[Guest]: know. But I can clearly see the reason why. And there's no, for example, Kashmir Pandya,

01:28:22.940 --> 01:28:28.700
[Guest]: it's very clear cut. It's a solid injustice which has been done against them. It's still not really

01:28:28.700 --> 01:28:33.340
[Guest]: been solved. It's still outside. And so this sort of resentment will obviously continue.

01:28:33.340 --> 01:28:36.780
[Amit Varma]: And another question too, I guess none of us will have an answer. And I don't know if you can

01:28:37.340 --> 01:28:41.740
[Amit Varma]: get metrics for that either is that as the generations pass and the memories of the forced

01:28:41.740 --> 01:28:48.620
[Amit Varma]: migration sort of grow dimmer, are you likely to see some kind of softening? And if not, does that

01:28:48.620 --> 01:28:54.460
[Amit Varma]: indicate that apart from the event, the resentments come from something more primal and tribal or

01:28:54.460 --> 01:28:59.740
[Guest]: whatever? Yeah, it's a good question. I have no clear answer, you know, for that. The cases we

01:28:59.740 --> 01:29:03.580
[Guest]: have in India, for example, the Parsis, the Baghdadi Jews, it's too long. I mean, we're

01:29:03.580 --> 01:29:08.460
[Guest]: talking many, many centuries. The more recent ones like the Tibetan refugees, whether internally

01:29:08.460 --> 01:29:13.820
[Guest]: displaced or even damned displaced projects. It's too recent. So I think it's kind of caught up

01:29:14.460 --> 01:29:19.100
[Guest]: in between having persecuted communities in India who have come very far and who have assimilated

01:29:19.100 --> 01:29:24.220
[Guest]: very well. And sort of groups which are much more recent and who are in the first or second generation.

01:29:24.780 --> 01:29:29.340
[Guest]: And maybe it's too early to tell. Maybe we know 50 years down the line how these groups are doing.

01:29:29.340 --> 01:29:33.900
[Amit Varma]: And one of the major points you make is that a lot of the forced migrations are not just because of

01:29:33.900 --> 01:29:38.380
[Amit Varma]: partitions or politics are also because of development projects where people are building

01:29:38.380 --> 01:29:43.100
[Guest]: dams and people... It's huge. The numbers are astonishing. As per one report. I mean, clearly

01:29:43.100 --> 01:29:46.700
[Guest]: more people have been displaced because of development induced projects cumulatively

01:29:47.260 --> 01:29:51.580
[Guest]: than all the partitions put together. The three partitions that I see in 1937, 47, 71,

01:29:52.540 --> 01:29:56.620
[Guest]: which is a crazy statistic, if you think about it, because partition was massive. I mean, you know,

01:29:56.620 --> 01:30:00.620
[Guest]: you have the images of the strains moving... Seven and a half million people. Absolutely.

01:30:00.620 --> 01:30:04.620
[Guest]: The Bangladeshi refugee crisis, 71, 10 million refugees in eight months.

01:30:05.260 --> 01:30:08.940
[Guest]: Districts having more refugees than the population of the district themselves.

01:30:08.940 --> 01:30:14.780
[Guest]: Short term though. And we're seeing cumulatively more than 40 million people have been displaced

01:30:14.780 --> 01:30:19.180
[Guest]: internally. So, and these are small displacements. This could be happening outside your house,

01:30:19.180 --> 01:30:24.460
[Guest]: a small busty being, you know, sent forcibly demolished and people are on the streets tomorrow.

01:30:24.460 --> 01:30:28.620
[Guest]: But when you actually count this across the country, it's quite a staggering number.

01:30:28.620 --> 01:30:31.900
[Guest]: And so for me, what's interesting is that often, for example, the Tibetan refugees,

01:30:32.620 --> 01:30:38.140
[Guest]: we've been more hospitable, or we've extended more privileges and rights to international

01:30:38.140 --> 01:30:42.940
[Guest]: refugees, because we've been under the scanner, than our own internally displaced,

01:30:43.580 --> 01:30:46.220
[Guest]: which is some sort of a sort of irony.

01:30:46.220 --> 01:30:51.340
[Amit Varma]: No, no. So it's also indicative of how these are normalized. Like you'd imagine 40 million people

01:30:51.340 --> 01:30:54.780
[Amit Varma]: and you know, we are a democracy, there would be some kind of movement around this, there would be

01:30:54.780 --> 01:30:58.700
[Guest]: a cry and so on. Yeah, but the 40 million is aggregation of many small ones. So we don't really

01:30:58.700 --> 01:31:02.300
[Amit Varma]: see it. Yeah, and they don't talk to each other. And it's just, oh, this is just my bad luck.

01:31:03.340 --> 01:31:07.180
[Guest]: Some of the dam incidents that I sort of read about were insane. I mean,

01:31:07.180 --> 01:31:10.860
[Guest]: some of them were literally flushed out. I mean, just one fine day, the water comes and you know,

01:31:10.860 --> 01:31:14.780
[Guest]: you're forced to leave. I think in Andhra Pradesh, you mentioned the government got

01:31:14.780 --> 01:31:18.540
[Guest]: confused about when the displacement would be finished. What is the timing of the flow of the

01:31:18.540 --> 01:31:23.260
[Guest]: water? Now, there's, of course, no doubt that a lot of these dams have also worked. There's

01:31:23.260 --> 01:31:27.980
[Guest]: good that's come out. But then you'd have to say that, you know, what has been, there has to be a

01:31:27.980 --> 01:31:34.140
[Guest]: way of, you know, I think it's been only very recent that this principle of rehabilitation

01:31:34.140 --> 01:31:38.780
[Guest]: has been enshrined. Earlier, you could pretty much do what you wanted. Some of the first big

01:31:38.780 --> 01:31:42.860
[Guest]: dams of India, unfortunately, we don't know what, you know, how they went about acquiring land or

01:31:42.860 --> 01:31:48.060
[Guest]: how they went about submerging. But clearly, there was no process, which means even if you take them,

01:31:48.060 --> 01:31:52.460
[Guest]: if these numbers will also increase, if you go before independence, if you start considering the

01:31:52.460 --> 01:31:57.020
[Guest]: really big dams in South India, for example, built in the early 20th century, celebrated today,

01:31:57.820 --> 01:32:00.700
[Guest]: but they must have submerged massive, massive amounts of land.

01:32:00.700 --> 01:32:05.020
[Amit Varma]: No, I have very little sympathy for sort of cost benefit analysis of this sort of thing,

01:32:05.020 --> 01:32:10.140
[Amit Varma]: because the cost is normally on one section of people disproportionately the poor and the benefit

01:32:10.140 --> 01:32:12.860
[Guest]: is somewhere. And we usually don't get the electricity, don't get the water.

01:32:14.140 --> 01:32:18.140
[Amit Varma]: The moral and humanitarian cost is huge to begin with. And then, you know, why would you

01:32:18.140 --> 01:32:22.460
[Amit Varma]: sort of look at benefits? You know, there are a lot of little things in your book,

01:32:22.460 --> 01:32:25.500
[Amit Varma]: which I wanted to talk about, but I've taken up a lot of your time. So I'll kind of go to

01:32:25.500 --> 01:32:31.420
[Amit Varma]: the bigger questions at the end. One of the very interesting contrasts you make about

01:32:31.420 --> 01:32:37.500
[Amit Varma]: attitudes towards migrations is the attitudes of Ambedkar, Gandhi, and Thackeray. Can you

01:32:37.500 --> 01:32:40.780
[Guest]: tell me a little bit more about that? Yeah, Thackeray comes across as this

01:32:40.780 --> 01:32:47.340
[Guest]: staunch nativist. Of course, he's a brilliant strategist. So he used opportunities for,

01:32:47.340 --> 01:32:53.180
[Guest]: you know, talking about migration. But like Trump, like any staunch nativist,

01:32:53.180 --> 01:32:58.700
[Guest]: basically saying your people first, immigrants are something to be looked against,

01:32:58.700 --> 01:33:02.300
[Guest]: often even attacked. You know, Shiv Sainik also attacked people on this issue.

01:33:03.100 --> 01:33:06.940
[Guest]: And it's sporadic, you know, I mean, in the sense that the violence is sporadic,

01:33:06.940 --> 01:33:13.740
[Guest]: but the basic ideology is that our people first. And when you think of cities as sites,

01:33:13.740 --> 01:33:19.260
[Guest]: it's strange, because Mumbai, for example, it's a city built by migrants for migrants,

01:33:19.260 --> 01:33:22.140
[Guest]: even today, about 60% of the population is migrant. Thackeray himself was a migrant.

01:33:22.140 --> 01:33:25.420
[Guest]: Thackeray himself was a migrant. And Thackeray's surname, for example,

01:33:25.420 --> 01:33:28.940
[Guest]: is anglicized. And, you know, he's got this... William Makepeace Bal Thackeray.

01:33:28.940 --> 01:33:32.460
[Guest]: Exactly. So, so it's and now his movie is being played by, you know,

01:33:32.460 --> 01:33:35.180
[Guest]: Nawazuddin. A Muslim migrant from UP. It just doesn't

01:33:35.180 --> 01:33:39.340
[Guest]: get more bizarre or ironic than... In fact, when you were growing up,

01:33:39.340 --> 01:33:42.700
[Amit Varma]: did you ever feel victimized by his tirades? Because you're from UDP, right? And you were

01:33:42.700 --> 01:33:48.380
[Guest]: in Mumbai. Yeah, so we have an interesting family story to this. Our surname, for example,

01:33:49.020 --> 01:33:56.060
[Guest]: is direct sort of fallout of this. We used to live in Shivaji Park. And I believe family,

01:33:56.060 --> 01:34:00.700
[Guest]: friends, I was not, of course, there at that time. But these are stories passed on in the family.

01:34:00.700 --> 01:34:04.220
[Guest]: And we used to, apparently, our building was neighboring Thackeray. So as you're all

01:34:04.220 --> 01:34:10.140
[Guest]: very cordial relations. And obviously, I mean, he was a very nice guy on a personal basis. So,

01:34:10.140 --> 01:34:15.100
[Guest]: you know, nobody had hard feelings against that. But in this whole anti South Indian movement in

01:34:15.100 --> 01:34:20.940
[Guest]: the 1960s, eventually, we actually had to rather strategically changed our surname.

01:34:20.940 --> 01:34:25.100
[Guest]: And we took this name Tumbe, because it sounds Maharashtrian. And so Tumbe, because there's a

01:34:25.100 --> 01:34:29.820
[Guest]: Tembe and a Tambe. But we're the only Tumbes in the world. You are literally the only Tumbe.

01:34:31.580 --> 01:34:34.380
[Guest]: Google it. There's nobody else. I will go on Facebook.

01:34:34.380 --> 01:34:40.060
[Guest]: And, yeah, so this is a remarkable story that thanks to the Thackerays, you know,

01:34:40.060 --> 01:34:47.420
[Guest]: we sort of changed our surname. And it's because he's got our surname changed. I mean, this,

01:34:47.420 --> 01:34:53.100
[Guest]: of course, in jest, because he didn't have a direct connection. The city's name has changed,

01:34:53.100 --> 01:34:58.940
[Guest]: but his surname has not. So yeah. And tell me also then a bit about...

01:34:59.580 --> 01:35:01.500
[Guest]: And I should say Tumbe is the name of a village in Udupi.

01:35:01.500 --> 01:35:07.580
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. Oh, right. Tell me also a bit about, you know, given that urbanization is basically a

01:35:07.580 --> 01:35:12.300
[Amit Varma]: process of migration. Tell me a bit about Ambedkar and Gandhi's views on contrasting

01:35:12.300 --> 01:35:16.940
[Amit Varma]: views on urbanization. Like you've quoted Ambedkar famously is calling the Indian village,

01:35:16.940 --> 01:35:21.660
[Amit Varma]: quote, a sink of localism, a den of ignorance, narrow mindedness and communalism,

01:35:21.660 --> 01:35:27.260
[Amit Varma]: stop quote. And Gandhi, perhaps inspired by Ruskin and Tolstoy and all those guys sort of

01:35:27.260 --> 01:35:31.580
[Amit Varma]: deified the village. And in fact, he seemed to I mean, if you read Hind Swaraj, for example, I had

01:35:31.580 --> 01:35:36.300
[Amit Varma]: a couple of episodes on Gandhi with Ram Guha where we discuss this almost seems to be against so much

01:35:36.300 --> 01:35:41.580
[Amit Varma]: of modernity, like railways, like doctors and whatever. But Gandhi's approach to urbanization

01:35:41.580 --> 01:35:48.220
[Amit Varma]: was sort of a complete contrast. And you've sort of very nicely exposed the counterplay between

01:35:48.220 --> 01:35:54.940
[Guest]: these three approaches. Yeah. Gandhi himself was a migrant. I don't think he had a opposition to

01:35:54.940 --> 01:35:59.020
[Guest]: migrants. And as I mentioned, he's on record saying that if people are being oppressed,

01:35:59.020 --> 01:36:04.220
[Guest]: then they should move. So he doesn't have a really problem with that. But I think his ultimate

01:36:04.940 --> 01:36:10.540
[Guest]: disdain for cities came about because I think he was more in sync with the village life. And also,

01:36:10.540 --> 01:36:15.660
[Guest]: I think at heart, he had this idea of being an environmentalist. I mean, he's not called

01:36:15.660 --> 01:36:20.780
[Guest]: an environmentalist then, but I think it's the harmony. And even today, you'll find this

01:36:20.780 --> 01:36:25.660
[Guest]: return to this idea of environmentalism that, you know, this rural life is much more,

01:36:25.660 --> 01:36:31.260
[Guest]: is less polluting, etc. In the book, I make my position very clear that I take the Ambedkarite

01:36:31.260 --> 01:36:36.460
[Guest]: view that India needs more urbanization, not less. More people have to move to cities.

01:36:36.460 --> 01:36:41.820
[Guest]: And ultimately, it's coming from Ambedkar's perspective. Because if you look at caste-wise

01:36:41.820 --> 01:36:47.420
[Guest]: urbanization, you know, people, if you look at social groups as these small concentric circles,

01:36:47.420 --> 01:36:53.020
[Guest]: it's the well-off have these wide spatial networks, their concentric circles span the world.

01:36:53.580 --> 01:36:59.020
[Guest]: And the social groups where these concentric circles just span a few villages. And if India

01:36:59.020 --> 01:37:04.860
[Guest]: really has to flourish, one, these concentric circles have to start interacting, but they also

01:37:04.860 --> 01:37:09.500
[Guest]: have to start widening. And that's what migration brings about. And so what India really needs is

01:37:09.500 --> 01:37:13.660
[Guest]: more rural to urban migration, of course, of the safe kind, not exploitative, and so on.

01:37:13.660 --> 01:37:21.500
[Guest]: But to have a blanket policy saying, you know, we should have reverse migration, or let's...

01:37:22.380 --> 01:37:27.660
[Guest]: And the other thing is, I think what people have failed in this Gandhian world of rural development

01:37:28.540 --> 01:37:33.740
[Guest]: is the basic flaw in the ideology that is rural development almost always gets more,

01:37:33.740 --> 01:37:37.900
[Guest]: gets you more migration. That is, as people get rich in rural areas, they actually leave.

01:37:38.700 --> 01:37:41.660
[Guest]: And you've seen this in coastal Andhra, where people became very rich,

01:37:41.660 --> 01:37:46.220
[Guest]: high productivity, and they start moving to Hyderabad, US, because as you get richer,

01:37:46.220 --> 01:37:49.740
[Guest]: you're not going to farm work, you're not going to do backbeating from, it's a basic.

01:37:49.740 --> 01:37:51.900
[Amit Varma]: And you want to be part of larger economic networks.

01:37:51.900 --> 01:37:58.300
[Guest]: Absolutely. So I'm not against rural development, obviously. But my sort of view is that with rural

01:37:58.300 --> 01:38:02.220
[Guest]: development, you will get more migration. And that should not be seen as a failure of what

01:38:02.220 --> 01:38:07.660
[Guest]: you're trying to do, but just as an inevitable part of a sort of development. And you see it in

01:38:07.660 --> 01:38:13.420
[Guest]: China, it's got tremendous benefits, people moving from villages to cities. And, you know,

01:38:13.420 --> 01:38:17.820
[Guest]: you're seeing it in India, it's still very slow in India, compared to in China, because as I say,

01:38:17.820 --> 01:38:22.220
[Guest]: in this book, the great Indian migration wave means people also go back. So it's not that

01:38:22.220 --> 01:38:26.460
[Guest]: people are coming and setting in Indian cities, a lot of them spend their life here, but they go

01:38:26.460 --> 01:38:34.620
[Guest]: back. So India, in a way, has an inbuilt check on permanent migration. I argue mostly it's coming

01:38:34.620 --> 01:38:40.380
[Guest]: from the source region, women are moving less. Some of it is also housing, high exorbitant costs,

01:38:40.380 --> 01:38:46.380
[Guest]: people can never really put a foot in the city. So these three views of the nativist, of the

01:38:46.940 --> 01:38:51.020
[Guest]: completely sort of celebratory account of migration, safe migration, which is Ambedkar,

01:38:51.020 --> 01:38:56.700
[Guest]: and Gandhi in the middle where he loves the idea of, you know, ideas moving about,

01:38:56.700 --> 01:39:04.140
[Guest]: or even people moving about. But fundamentally, the focus is always on the village. And if possible,

01:39:04.140 --> 01:39:08.060
[Guest]: there should be no cities, everyone should be living in the village. And Ambedkar would never

01:39:08.060 --> 01:39:14.300
[Guest]: support that. And the three positions are, for me, very fascinating. And for Ambedkar, of course,

01:39:15.100 --> 01:39:19.980
[Guest]: the crux of this was caste in the sense that if you move to the city, you would sort of weaken

01:39:19.980 --> 01:39:24.460
[Guest]: your caste in it. Now, it's a good question to ask, has caste really disappeared once you move

01:39:24.460 --> 01:39:29.820
[Guest]: to the city? And I don't think so. But I would argue it's less. I think that that's the whole

01:39:29.820 --> 01:39:34.620
[Amit Varma]: point. When you talk about urbanization, it's not a panacea for anything. There's no magic pill.

01:39:34.620 --> 01:39:38.380
[Amit Varma]: But as you point out in your book, if you're travelling on the crowded Virar local, you don't

01:39:38.380 --> 01:39:42.460
[Guest]: have time to see what the caste of the guy next to you is. It is relatively less. And there's a

01:39:42.460 --> 01:39:48.380
[Guest]: lot of evidence now suggests that the anonymity, it helps our entrepreneurship, it has a variety

01:39:48.380 --> 01:39:53.020
[Guest]: of things. So overall, this this romantic idea, which policymakers in India have had for a long

01:39:53.020 --> 01:39:58.140
[Guest]: time, that is, you know, if we do enough in rural areas, people won't have to move.

01:39:58.140 --> 01:40:03.500
[Guest]: have to move, is fundamentally flawed. In fact, if you do enough in rural areas,

01:40:03.500 --> 01:40:08.060
[Guest]: people will still move. And the rural areas will also then consolidate into urban areas.

01:40:08.060 --> 01:40:12.540
[Guest]: Absolutely. Yeah. And which is happening, you know, you see these small townships and so on

01:40:12.540 --> 01:40:16.940
[Amit Varma]: emerging. Right. You know, one of the very interesting things that you say in your book,

01:40:17.500 --> 01:40:22.940
[Amit Varma]: which kind of seems obvious now in the light of current events, but if you told me this 15 years

01:40:22.940 --> 01:40:27.020
[Amit Varma]: ago, it would have seemed very counterintuitive. And I would have said no way, which is that just

01:40:27.020 --> 01:40:31.260
[Amit Varma]: as you point out the major ideological battle of the 20th century was between capitalism and

01:40:31.260 --> 01:40:36.380
[Amit Varma]: communism, your sense is that in the 21st century is likely to be between cosmopolitanism and

01:40:36.380 --> 01:40:41.660
[Amit Varma]: nativism, which we see playing out all around us, but is nevertheless still a little surprising to

01:40:41.660 --> 01:40:46.620
[Amit Varma]: me, because you'd imagine that as we become more urbanized and cosmopolitan and globalized,

01:40:46.620 --> 01:40:50.220
[Amit Varma]: there'll be less chance for nativism to rear its ugly head.

01:40:50.220 --> 01:40:54.620
[Guest]: Actually, I mean, this is not completely new. I think I mean, I use that sentence,

01:40:54.620 --> 01:40:58.620
[Guest]: just because in the 20th century, capitalism can be very strong. But you did for a brief

01:40:58.620 --> 01:41:02.620
[Guest]: moment in the early 20th century, also have this battle between nativism and cosmopolitanism. For

01:41:02.620 --> 01:41:06.460
[Guest]: example, after the Great Depression, or actually after the First World War, there were these

01:41:06.460 --> 01:41:13.100
[Guest]: massive racist visa walls that emerged, blocking off, you know, migration flows in Europe and US.

01:41:13.100 --> 01:41:18.060
[Guest]: So this is not the first time, and there have been people like Trump before. But because this

01:41:18.060 --> 01:41:22.460
[Guest]: economic ideological battle is pretty much done and dusted with, there might be new ones which

01:41:22.460 --> 01:41:28.060
[Guest]: might emerge in the century. And because we have this massive backlash against globalization,

01:41:28.860 --> 01:41:33.740
[Guest]: remember, it's more backlash against globalization of people. There is, of course,

01:41:33.740 --> 01:41:39.660
[Guest]: the trade war and the capital flow war. But between the movement of people, goods and money,

01:41:39.660 --> 01:41:46.700
[Guest]: or capital, political sort of position is towards the first, slightly less against the second.

01:41:46.700 --> 01:41:51.020
[Guest]: And on capital, nobody's talking about stopping capital flows. Everyone loves that. But it's

01:41:51.020 --> 01:41:56.380
[Guest]: the people which people have a problem against. And so, you know, I mean, this is a battle that's

01:41:56.380 --> 01:42:00.940
[Guest]: going to really rage on. And we've seen it in all the elections across the world. In India,

01:42:00.940 --> 01:42:05.660
[Guest]: where immigration is such a huge issue, it was never a political issue for a central election.

01:42:05.660 --> 01:42:12.300
[Guest]: This time, you know, it also mattered to some extent. And so I argue that, of course,

01:42:12.940 --> 01:42:18.700
[Guest]: there's a bias. I myself happened to be born in Mumbai, cosmopolitan city of India, maybe Asia.

01:42:18.700 --> 01:42:23.500
[Guest]: But I in this book is a celebratory account of cosmopolitan. It's a defense of that.

01:42:24.140 --> 01:42:29.100
[Guest]: We benefit from ideas transferring. Some of these ideas may not be good, but, you know,

01:42:29.100 --> 01:42:33.260
[Guest]: you might even have counter ideas coming from these exchange flows. And I think history serves

01:42:33.260 --> 01:42:38.220
[Guest]: as a nice reminder that especially for social groups to rise, migration is very important.

01:42:38.220 --> 01:42:43.260
[Guest]: And if not for any other reason, I think that's one of the reasons why one should support mobility.

01:42:43.260 --> 01:42:48.860
[Amit Varma]: Towards the end of your book, you start off by saying that there are at least three major

01:42:48.860 --> 01:42:52.700
[Amit Varma]: developments that you foresee in the 21st century. Tell me about them.

01:42:52.700 --> 01:42:57.340
[Guest]: So the first, of course, is the North to South migration. This has started in bits,

01:42:58.620 --> 01:43:04.460
[Guest]: but it's going to increase. And the reason is because the earlier linguistic barrier,

01:43:05.100 --> 01:43:08.460
[Guest]: Hindi speakers trying to learn South Indian language is kind of broken,

01:43:08.460 --> 01:43:13.660
[Guest]: partly because now the wage difference is so high that people don't mind learning these languages.

01:43:13.660 --> 01:43:18.380
[Guest]: And so you're finding, you know, Bhojpuri Bengali speakers who are learning Tamil or learning Malayalam

01:43:18.380 --> 01:43:21.980
[Guest]: or who are working without these languages because they're desperate for good wages

01:43:21.980 --> 01:43:26.540
[Guest]: and they're getting very good wages. The added benefit being that the South has better labor laws.

01:43:27.100 --> 01:43:30.700
[Guest]: So they're actually also getting better labor protection than working in say, Gujarat or Maharashtra.

01:43:30.700 --> 01:43:32.780
[Amit Varma]: It's practically the opposite of Hindi imposition.

01:43:32.780 --> 01:43:41.500
[Guest]: Yeah, absolutely. So they're getting a good deal by migration. Now, you might get a backlash.

01:43:41.500 --> 01:43:46.940
[Guest]: So you have like you have this, the Kannada Rakshika Vedic in Bangalore. Until now,

01:43:46.940 --> 01:43:51.580
[Guest]: you've not seen any political movements against migrants, thankfully. But this is definitely a

01:43:51.580 --> 01:43:56.620
[Guest]: feature. And so the great Indian migration wave, which I argue went East 19th century, West 20th

01:43:56.620 --> 01:44:01.820
[Guest]: century, is now going South. Then there's a point of climate, climate change. And you're seeing

01:44:01.820 --> 01:44:07.100
[Guest]: crazy temperature variations. It's going to affect agriculture. Historically, migration has obviously

01:44:07.100 --> 01:44:12.460
[Guest]: been linked. Even the Arthashastra has a mention of what kingdoms should do in terms of famine,

01:44:12.460 --> 01:44:17.820
[Guest]: move the kingdom to another place and so on. So that's, you know, very climate change, especially

01:44:17.820 --> 01:44:24.060
[Guest]: because the flooding, you know, if the sea levels rise and so on, Bangladesh is a low-lying place.

01:44:24.060 --> 01:44:30.540
[Guest]: And so that's like a, you know, huge hotspot of migration. And third is, of course, also

01:44:30.540 --> 01:44:35.660
[Guest]: expats, you know, of international immigrants coming into India. And so far, we've had Nepalis

01:44:35.660 --> 01:44:42.620
[Guest]: and Bangladeshis in large numbers. But with India growing, you'll also see immigrants coming from

01:44:42.620 --> 01:44:49.180
[Guest]: Europe and US. You see that in a few cities, but it's still in the few thousands. And this could

01:44:49.180 --> 01:44:53.820
[Guest]: dramatically grow up in 2050. You might find, you know, walking down the street in Bombay,

01:44:54.380 --> 01:44:59.180
[Guest]: and you might find literally a lot of races, which you're not seeing today. In a way, it would be a

01:44:59.180 --> 01:45:01.980
[Guest]: in a way, it would be a return to the late 19th century.

01:45:01.980 --> 01:45:04.540
[Amit Varma]: Maybe Thackeray's descendants could meet other Thackeray's.

01:45:04.540 --> 01:45:10.620
[Guest]: Yeah, you never know. They could also marry outside. You'll have a transnational family.

01:45:10.620 --> 01:45:15.020
[Guest]: Yeah, you never know. But Bombay was so cosmopolitan. When you read Bombay's history,

01:45:15.020 --> 01:45:19.580
[Guest]: late 19th century, you had communities from across the world in Bombay. And you could probably see

01:45:19.580 --> 01:45:21.900
[Amit Varma]: that again in the next 50 years.

01:45:21.900 --> 01:45:25.340
[Amit Varma]: Makes me feel even better about living in and loving the city.

01:45:25.340 --> 01:45:25.980
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

01:45:25.980 --> 01:45:32.140
[Amit Varma]: One final question. Did the process of writing this book change how you look at India?

01:45:32.140 --> 01:45:36.940
[Guest]: Yeah, absolutely. I mean, I've always loved this place because it just,

01:45:36.940 --> 01:45:41.500
[Guest]: I mean, it's cliched. But it is true that it's just so beautifully diverse. And

01:45:41.500 --> 01:45:45.020
[Guest]: we just learn something every day. I think Ram Gowar said that, you know, this is

01:45:45.020 --> 01:45:48.860
[Guest]: the most fascinating country, something like that. And I completely agree. And I have had

01:45:48.860 --> 01:45:53.500
[Guest]: the opportunity to travel a fair bit in the world. And every time you travel in India,

01:45:53.500 --> 01:45:59.980
[Guest]: it's just something new that, you know, opens up. Writing history, especially for a general audience,

01:45:59.980 --> 01:46:06.060
[Guest]: has been really fun and also a real eye opener. Because there are many aspects of history where,

